mp-2">Summary</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Acknowledgements</span></div><div data-state="closed" data-orientation="vertical" data-slot="accordion-item" class="border-foreground/10 last:border-b-0 border-b-0"><h3 data-orientation="vertical" data-state="closed" class="flex"><button type="button" aria-controls="radix-_R_6banpfqt6btb_" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" data-orientation="vertical" id="radix-_R_2banpfqt6btb_" data-slot="accordion-trigger" class="focus-visible:border-ring focus-visible:ring-ring/50 flex flex-1 items-start justify-between gap-4 rounded-md text-left transition-all outline-none focus-visible:ring-[3px] disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 [&amp;[data-state=open]&gt;svg]:rotate-180 w-full py-0.75 font-light text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer" data-radix-collection-item=""><span class="line-clamp-2">Introduction</span><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-chevron-down text-muted-foreground pointer-events-none size-4 shrink-0 translate-y-0.5 transition-transform duration-200"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"></path></svg></button></h3><div data-state="closed" id="radix-_R_6banpfqt6btb_" hidden="" role="region" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2banpfqt6btb_" data-orientation="vertical" data-slot="accordion-content" class="data-[state=closed]:animate-accordion-up data-[state=open]:animate-accordion-down overflow-hidden text-sm" style="--radix-accordion-content-height:var(--radix-collapsible-content-height);--radix-accordion-content-width:var(--radix-collapsible-content-width)"></div></div></div><div data-orientation="horizontal" role="none" class="shrink-0 bg-border h-[1px] w-full my-4"></div><div data-slot="accordion" class="" data-orientation="vertical"><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2 font-bold">The Translation</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Colophon</span></div></div><div data-orientation="horizontal" role="none" class="shrink-0 bg-border h-[1px] w-full my-4"></div><div data-slot="accordion" class="" data-orientation="vertical"><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Notes</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Glossary</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Bibliography</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><script>$RS=function(a,b){a=document.getElementById(a);b=document.getElementById(b);for(a.parentNode.removeChild(a);a.firstChild;)b.parentNode.insertBefore(a.firstChild,b);b.parentNode.removeChild(b)};$RS("S:3","P:3")</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"1f:I[411156,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fb4b456dae69409.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/6165fecb8e0eae36.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1cfd6a6ab8fe5d2f.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/15d7387d42764915.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\"],\"ReaderBackMatterPanel\"]\n20:T8fb,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The short version of The Heart Sūtra was first compiled‍—most likely as an abstract of longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras‍—in China sometime in the middle of the seventh century ᴄᴇ. Shortly thereafter, it appears that the sūtra was translated from Chinese into Sanskrit. The material used to compile the sūtra was extracted from key passages in Prajñāpāramitā scriptures in Chinese translation, especially Kumārajīva’s (344–413 ᴄᴇ) translation of The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines (Taishō 223). These central statements were then framed by an introduction describing the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara’s role as the teacher, and then a concluding mantra, which functioned to encapsulate the blessings of the Prajñāpāramitā teachings. In this way, the short version of The Heart Sūtra combines established Buddhist Prajñāpāramitā scripture with dhāraṇī practice in an abridged format that is eminently suited for recitation. Notably, at that time in China such scriptural digests summarizing the words of the Buddha (buddhavacana) were common, and The Heart Sūtra is certainly not unique in this way. What is remarkable, however, is the immense importance and popularity the short version of The Heart Sūtra came to enjoy in China and the rest of East Asia. When viewed from the perspective of its roots in Prajñāpāramitā literature and its transformative and liberating efficacy in the perception of its many devotees, The Heart Sūtra does fulfill important criteria for being a genuine Buddhist scripture. For example, the Mahāyāna sūtra Inspiring Determination (Adhyāśayasañcodana, Toh 69) defines authentic buddhavacana as any discourse that fulfils the following four criteria: (1) it must be meaningful, (2) it has to be consistent with the Dharma, (3) it should reduce mental defilements, and (4) it should present the qualities of nirvāṇa as opposed to saṃsāra. In this sense The Heart Sūtra is perhaps not so different from many other Mahāyāna scriptures, in particular those of the Prajñāpāramitā family, that likewise were transmitted across a variety of time periods, regions, cultures, and languages‍—constantly in flux, yet ever encapsulating the transcendent aspects of authentic buddhavacana."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"21:T8fb,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The short version of The Heart Sūtra was first compiled‍—most likely as an abstract of longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras‍—in China sometime in the middle of the seventh century ᴄᴇ. Shortly thereafter, it appears that the sūtra was translated from Chinese into Sanskrit. The material used to compile the sūtra was extracted from key passages in Prajñāpāramitā scriptures in Chinese translation, especially Kumārajīva’s (344–413 ᴄᴇ) translation of The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines (Taishō 223). These central statements were then framed by an introduction describing the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara’s role as the teacher, and then a concluding mantra, which functioned to encapsulate the blessings of the Prajñāpāramitā teachings. In this way, the short version of The Heart Sūtra combines established Buddhist Prajñāpāramitā scripture with dhāraṇī practice in an abridged format that is eminently suited for recitation. Notably, at that time in China such scriptural digests summarizing the words of the Buddha (buddhavacana) were common, and The Heart Sūtra is certainly not unique in this way. What is remarkable, however, is the immense importance and popularity the short version of The Heart Sūtra came to enjoy in China and the rest of East Asia. When viewed from the perspective of its roots in Prajñāpāramitā literature and its transformative and liberating efficacy in the perception of its many devotees, The Heart Sūtra does fulfill important criteria for being a genuine Buddhist scripture. For example, the Mahāyāna sūtra Inspiring Determination (Adhyāśayasañcodana, Toh 69) defines authentic buddhavacana as any discourse that fulfils the following four criteria: (1) it must be meaningful, (2) it has to be consistent with the Dharma, (3) it should reduce mental defilements, and (4) it should present the qualities of nirvāṇa as opposed to saṃsāra. In this sense The Heart Sūtra is perhaps not so different from many other Mahāyāna scriptures, in particular those of the Prajñāpāramitā family, that likewise were transmitted across a variety of time periods, regions, cultures, and languages‍—constantly in flux, yet ever encapsulating the transcendent aspects of authentic buddhavacana."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"22:T8fb,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The short version of The Heart Sūtra was first compiled‍—most likely as an abstract of longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras‍—in China sometime in the middle of the seventh century ᴄᴇ. Shortly thereafter, it appears that the sūtra was translated from Chinese into Sanskrit. The material used to compile the sūtra was extracted from key passages in Prajñāpāramitā scriptures in Chinese translation, especially Kumārajīva’s (344–413 ᴄᴇ) translation of The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines (Taishō 223). These central statements were then framed by an introduction describing the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara’s role as the teacher, and then a concluding mantra, which functioned to encapsulate the blessings of the Prajñāpāramitā teachings. In this way, the short version of The Heart Sūtra combines established Buddhist Prajñāpāramitā scripture with dhāraṇī practice in an abridged format that is eminently suited for recitation. Notably, at that time in China such scriptural digests summarizing the words of the Buddha (buddhavacana) were common, and The Heart Sūtra is certainly not unique in this way. What is remarkable, however, is the immense importance and popularity the short version of The Heart Sūtra came to enjoy in China and the rest of East Asia. When viewed from the perspective of its roots in Prajñāpāramitā literature and its transformative and liberating efficacy in the perception of its many devotees, The Heart Sūtra does fulfill important criteria for being a genuine Buddhist scripture. For example, the Mahāyāna sūtra Inspiring Determination (Adhyāśayasañcodana, Toh 69) defines authentic buddhavacana as any discourse that fulfils the following four criteria: (1) it must be meaningful, (2) it has to be consistent with the Dharma, (3) it should reduce mental defilements, and (4) it should present the qualities of nirvāṇa as opposed to saṃsāra. In this sense The Heart Sūtra is perhaps not so different from many other Mahāyāna scriptures, in particular those of the Prajñāpāramitā family, that likewise were transmitted across a variety of time periods, regions, cultures, and languages‍—constantly in flux, yet ever encapsulating the transcendent aspects of authentic buddhavacana."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"23:T8fb,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The short version of The Heart Sūtra was first compiled‍—most likely as an abstract of longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras‍—in China sometime in the middle of the seventh century ᴄᴇ. Shortly thereafter, it appears that the sūtra was translated from Chinese into Sanskrit. The material used to compile the sūtra was extracted from key passages in Prajñāpāramitā scriptures in Chinese translation, especially Kumārajīva’s (344–413 ᴄᴇ) translation of The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines (Taishō 223). These central statements were then framed by an introduction describing the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara’s role as the teacher, and then a concluding mantra, which functioned to encapsulate the blessings of the Prajñāpāramitā teachings. In this way, the short version of The Heart Sūtra combines established Buddhist Prajñāpāramitā scripture with dhāraṇī practice in an abridged format that is eminently suited for recitation. Notably, at that time in China such scriptural digests summarizing the words of the Buddha (buddhavacana) were common, and The Heart Sūtra is certainly not unique in this way. What is remarkable, however, is the immense importance and popularity the short version of The Heart Sūtra came to enjoy in China and the rest of East Asia. When viewed from the perspective of its roots in Prajñāpāramitā literature and its transformative and liberating efficacy in the perception of its many devotees, The Heart Sūtra does fulfill important criteria for being a genuine Buddhist scripture. For example, the Mahāyāna sūtra Inspiring Determination (Adhyāśayasañcodana, Toh 69) defines authentic buddhavacana as any discourse that fulfils the following four criteria: (1) it must be meaningful, (2) it has to be consistent with the Dharma, (3) it should reduce mental defilements, and (4) it should present the qualities of nirvāṇa as opposed to saṃsāra. In this sense The Heart Sūtra is perhaps not so different from many other Mahāyāna scriptures, in particular those of the Prajñāpāramitā family, that likewise were transmitted across a variety of time periods, regions, cultures, and languages‍—constantly in flux, yet ever encapsulating the transcendent aspects of authentic buddhavacana."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"24:T8fb,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The short version of The Heart Sūtra was first compiled‍—most likely as an abstract of longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras‍—in China sometime in the middle of the seventh century ᴄᴇ. Shortly thereafter, it appears that the sūtra was translated from Chinese into Sanskrit. The material used to compile the sūtra was extracted from key passages in Prajñāpāramitā scriptures in Chinese translation, especially Kumārajīva’s (344–413 ᴄᴇ) translation of The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines (Taishō 223). These central statements were then framed by an introduction describing the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara’s role as the teacher, and then a concluding mantra, which functioned to encapsulate the blessings of the Prajñāpāramitā teachings. In this way, the short version of The Heart Sūtra combines established Buddhist Prajñāpāramitā scripture with dhāraṇī practice in an abridged format that is eminently suited for recitation. Notably, at that time in China such scriptural digests summarizing the words of the Buddha (buddhavacana) were common, and The Heart Sūtra is certainly not unique in this way. What is remarkable, however, is the immense importance and popularity the short version of The Heart Sūtra came to enjoy in China and the rest of East Asia. When viewed from the perspective of its roots in Prajñāpāramitā literature and its transformative and liberating efficacy in the perception of its many devotees, The Heart Sūtra does fulfill important criteria for being a genuine Buddhist scripture. For example, the Mahāyāna sūtra Inspiring Determination (Adhyāśayasañcodana, Toh 69) defines authentic buddhavacana as any discourse that fulfils the following four criteria: (1) it must be meaningful, (2) it has to be consistent with the Dharma, (3) it should reduce mental defilements, and (4) it should present the qualities of nirvāṇa as opposed to saṃsāra. In this sense The Heart Sūtra is perhaps not so different from many other Mahāyāna scriptures, in particular those of the Prajñāpāramitā family, that likewise were transmitted across a variety of time periods, regions, cultures, and languages‍—constantly in flux, yet ever encapsulating the transcendent aspects of authentic buddhavacana."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"25:T419,In terms of Sanskrit sources, the first rendering of the short sūtra in Sanskrit was likely produced shortly after the compilation of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese in the middle of the seventh century. However, the earliest witness we have of a Sanskrit text is not an actual Sanskrit manuscript, but rather a version with the Sanskrit transliterated into Chinese characters (Taishō 256). This text was likely produced by the famous translator and teacher Amoghavajra (705–74) and can therefore be dated to the eighth century. While multiple Sanskrit manuscripts of the shorter version of The Heart Sūtra exist, any dating of such manuscripts is typically fraught with much uncertainty. Scholars have, however, dated a Sanskrit manuscript of the short version (currently kept in Tokyo National Museum) to the ninth or tenth century, and this appears to be the earliest extant Sanskrit manuscript. Tibetan translations of the short sūtra were never included in any of the Kangyurs, but several have been identified among the Dunhuang manuscripts.26:T419,In terms of Sanskrit sources, the first rendering of the short sūtra in Sanskrit was likely produced shortly after the compilation of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese in the middle of the seventh century. However, the earliest witness we have of a Sanskrit text is not an actual Sanskrit manuscript, but rather a version with the Sanskrit transliterated into Chinese characters (Taishō 256). This text was likely produced by the famous translator and teacher Amoghavajra (705–74) and can therefore be dated to the eighth century. While multiple Sanskrit manuscripts of the shorter version of The Heart Sūtra exist, any dating of such manuscripts is typically fraught with much uncertainty. Scholars have, however, dated a Sanskrit manuscript of the short version (currently kept in Tokyo National Museum) to the ninth or tenth century, and this appears to be the earliest extant Sanskrit manuscript. Tibetan translations of the short sūtra were never included in any of the Kangyurs, but several have been identified among the Dunhuang manuscripts.27:T419,In terms of Sanskrit sources, the first rendering of the short sūtra in Sanskrit was likely produced shortly after the compilation of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese in the middle of the seventh century. However, the earliest witness we have of a Sanskrit text is not an actual Sanskrit manuscript, but rather a version with the Sanskrit transliterated into Chinese characters (Taishō 256). This text was likely produced by the famous translator and teacher Amoghavajra (705–74) and can therefore be dated to the eighth century. While multiple Sanskrit manuscripts of the shorter version of The Heart Sūtra exist, any dating of such manuscripts is typically fraught with much uncertainty. Scholars have, however, dated a Sanskrit manuscript of the short version (currently kept in Tokyo National Museum) to the ninth or tenth century, and this appears to be the earliest extant Sanskrit manuscript. Tibetan translations of the short sūtra were never included in any of the Kangyurs, but several have been identified among the Dunhuang manuscripts.28:T419,In terms of Sanskrit sources, the first rendering of the short sūtra in Sanskrit was likely produced shortly after the compilation of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese in the middle of the seventh century. However, the earliest witness we have of a Sanskrit text is not an actual Sanskrit manuscript, but rather a version with the Sanskrit transliterated into Chinese characters (Taishō 256). This text was likely produced by the famous translator and teacher Amoghavajra (705–74) and can therefore be dated to the eighth century. While multiple Sanskrit manuscripts of the shorter version of The Heart Sūtra exist, any dating of such manuscripts is typically fraught with much uncertainty. Scholars have, however, dated a Sanskrit manuscript of the short version (currently kept in Tokyo National Museum) to the ninth or tenth century, and this appears to be the earliest extant Sanskrit manuscript. Tibetan translati"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ons of the short sūtra were never included in any of the Kangyurs, but several have been identified among the Dunhuang manuscripts.29:T46c,In sum, we can conclude that the Chinese version of the short sūtra must have been compiled sometime between 404 (when Kumārajīva completed his translation of Taishō 223) and 661 ᴄᴇ (the date on the stone stele), and that the Sanskrit translation was produced soon thereafter. However, in addition to these mutually distant historical markers, we also have data that place the likely time of compilation much more precisely within just a two-year period from 654–56 ᴄᴇ. First, 654 ᴄᴇ marks the year when the Dhāraṇī­samuccaya (Taishō 901), which is the likely source of the mantra in The Heart Sūtra, was translated into Chinese. Second, in Xuanzang’s biography (Taishō 2053, written in the late seventh century) it is mentioned that in 656 Xuanzang offered a gold-lettered version of The Heart Sūtra to the imperial family as a gift. Although the biography is a later source than the stone stele, the date provided in the biography is the earliest placement of The Heart Sūtra in the historical record and this may possibly be the very occasion on which The Heart Sūtra was first compiled in Chinese.2a:T46c,In sum, we can conclude that the Chinese version of the short sūtra must have been compiled sometime between 404 (when Kumārajīva completed his translation of Taishō 223) and 661 ᴄᴇ (the date on the stone stele), and that the Sanskrit translation was produced soon thereafter. However, in addition to these mutually distant historical markers, we also have data that place the likely time of compilation much more precisely within just a two-year period from 654–56 ᴄᴇ. First, 654 ᴄᴇ marks the year when the Dhāraṇī­samuccaya (Taishō 901), which is the likely source of the mantra in The Heart Sūtra, was translated into Chinese. Second, in Xuanzang’s biography (Taishō 2053, written in the late seventh century) it is mentioned that in 656 Xuanzang offered a gold-lettered version of The Heart Sūtra to the imperial family as a gift. Although the biography is a later source than the stone stele, the date provided in the biography is the earliest placement of The Heart Sūtra in the historical record and this may possibly be the very occasion on which The Heart Sūtra was first compiled in Chinese.2b:T46c,In sum, we can conclude that the Chinese version of the short sūtra must have been compiled sometime between 404 (when Kumārajīva completed his translation of Taishō 223) and 661 ᴄᴇ (the date on the stone stele), and that the Sanskrit translation was produced soon thereafter. However, in addition to these mutually distant historical markers, we also have data that place the likely time of compilation much more precisely within just a two-year period from 654–56 ᴄᴇ. First, 654 ᴄᴇ marks the year when the Dhāraṇī­samuccaya (Taishō 901), which is the likely source of the mantra in The Heart Sūtra, was translated into Chinese. Second, in Xuanzang’s biography (Taishō 2053, written in the late seventh century) it is mentioned that in 656 Xuanzang offered a gold-lettered version of The Heart Sūtra to the imperial family as a gift. Although the biography is a later source than the stone stele, the date provided in the biography is the earliest placement of The Heart Sūtra in the historical record and this may possibly be the very occasion on which The Heart Sūtra was first compiled in Chinese.2c:T408,It therefore appears that the history of the long sūtra can be told largely as a Sino-Tibetan exchange of ideas and manuscripts, which unfolded during the eighth to the eleventh century. In this regard, there are strong indications that the Dunhuang region was an important center for the exchange of such ideas and manuscripts. Among the scriptural treasures discovered in the Dunhuang caves in the early twentieth century, all of which must date prior to the turn of the eleventh century when the caves at Dunhuang were sealed off, t"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"here are numerous manuscripts of The Heart Sūtra in both Chinese and Tibetan. In addition to the shorter versions mentioned above, there are a number of longer versions, and apparently even a few “hybrid” manuscripts that are neither of the standard short or long sūtras. Like the Chinese and Sanskrit versions, these Tibetan Dunhuang manuscripts provide a variety of readings, but so far no comparative analyses of these texts, or critical editions of the manuscripts, have been published."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"18:[\"$\",\"$L1f\",null,{\"abbreviations\":[],\"bibliography\":[{\"heading\":\"Tibetan Canonical Texts\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"7e1dfdcd-beaa-434c-8496-baa971f90caf\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003ebcom ldan ’das ma shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po bam po gcig go\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 21, Degé Kangyur vol. 34 (sher phyin, ka), folios 144b–146a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"1595a411-a9e2-4e96-ba6e-27f511e77904\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003ebcom ldan ’das ma shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po bam po gcig go\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 531, Degé Kangyur vol. 88 (rgyud, na), folios 77b–78b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"3287ad36-71dd-4e3f-bc51-920ec7a66c9f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po\u003c/em\u003e. Stok no. 28, Stok Palace Kangyur vol. 51 (sras sna tshogs, ka), folios 277a–278b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"d21c265e-05be-44b7-8ae1-c0516348d26e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDenkarma (\u003cem\u003epho brang stod thang ldan [/ lhan] dkar gyi chos ’gyur ro cog gi dkar chag\u003c/em\u003e). Degé Tengyur vol. 206 (sna tshogs, jo), folios 294b–310a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Secondary Sources\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"ae29dfd6-905c-4f79-863f-3a6208aa3a82\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “Heart Murmurs: Some Problems with Conze’s Prajñāpāramitā-hṛdaya.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 8 (2015): 28–48. \u003ca href=\\\"http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/104\\\"\u003ehttp://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/104\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"7abdff0d-b458-43c3-b38d-4e2b26867337\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “Epithets of the Mantra in the Heart Sutra.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 12 (2017a): 26–57. \u003ca href=\\\"http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/155\\\"\u003ehttp://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/155\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"840843a2-07ab-498a-b9c6-7ee099ad1986\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “Form is (Not) Emptiness: The Enigma at the Heart of the Heart Sutra.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 13 (2017b): 52–80. \u003ca href=\\\"http://www.jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/164\\\"\u003ehttp://www.jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/164\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"206cfd27-7d8d-4e7c-b01b-28c1de36160a\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “The Buddhas of the Three Times and the Chinese Origins of the Heart Sutra.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 15 (2018): 9–27. \u003ca href=\\\"http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/184\\\"\u003ehttp://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/184\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4450fb27-d314-4ec5-8741-07bce6db3494\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “Xuanzang’s Relationship to the Heart Sūtra in Light of the Fangshan Stele.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of Chinese Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 32 (2019): 1–30. \u003ca href=\\\"http://chinesebuddhiststudies.org/previous_issues/jcbs3201_Attwood(1-30).pdf\\\"\u003ehttp://chinesebuddhiststudies.org/previous_issues/jcbs3201_Attwood(1-30).pdf\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"c333fce7-6c05-4733-bac9-c3dba494f3d2\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “The History of the Heart Sutra as a Palimpsest.” \u003cem\u003ePacific World\u003c/em\u003e, Series Four, no. 1 (2020): 155–82.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"74919c7e-08b6-4ece-b3d1-f37b4f5b90b0\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eAttwood, Jayarava. “Preliminary Notes on the Extended Heart Sutra in Chinese.” \u003cem\u003eAsian Literature and Translation\u003c/em\u003e 8 (1) (2021): 63–85. \u003ca href=\\\"https://alt.cardiffuniversitypress.org/articles/abstract/10.18573/alt.53/\\\"\u003ehttps://alt.cardiffuniversitypress.org/articles/abstract/10.18573/alt.53/\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"5ba33073-1cae-4b99-a880-fc908a1a99d4\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eConze, Edward. “The Prajñāpāramitā-Hṛdaya Sūtra.” In \u003cem\u003eThirty Years of Buddhist Studies: Selected Essays\u003c/em\u003e, 147–67. Bruno Cassirer, 1967.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"80f746ba-74a5-44e9-acb5-01242af95b7d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDalai Lama. \u003cem\u003eEssence of the Heart Sutra: The Dalai Lama’s Heart of Wisdom Teachings\u003c/em\u003e. Translated and edited by Geshe Thupten Jinpa. Sommerville: Wisdom Publications, 2015.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"8514edb1-2218-4d03-8439-4bf749e3502e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eHerrmann-Pfandt, Adelheid. \u003cem\u003eDie lHan kar ma: ein früher Katalog der ins Tibetische übersetzten buddhistischen Texte\u003c/em\u003e. Vienna: Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, 2008.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b90921ed-0715-4038-91d4-bd72d6b6e1e6\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eHoriuchi, Toshio. “Revisiting the ‘Indian’ Commentaries on the Prajñāpāramitāhṛdaya: Vimalamitra’s Interpretation of the ‘Eight Aspects.’ ” \u003cem\u003eActa Asiatica\u003c/em\u003e 121 (2021): 53–81.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"f6300dd1-742c-4a21-815d-49045bff8610\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eShi, Huifeng. “Apocryphal Treatment for Conze’s Heart Problems: ‘Non-attainment,’ ‘Apprehension,’ and ‘Mental Hanging’ in the Prajñāpāramitā.” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 6 (2014): 72–105. \u003ca href=\\\"http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/75\\\"\u003ehttp://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/75\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"67ede31f-85a6-4a4d-a916-06501afa86e0\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eIshii, Kōsei (\u003cem\u003e石井 公成\u003c/em\u003e). \u003cem\u003e『般若心経』をめぐる諸問題 : ジャン・ナティエ氏の玄奘創作説を疑う\u003c/em\u003e [Issues Surrounding the Prajñāpāramitā-hṛdaya: Doubts Concerning Jan Nattier’s Theory of a Composition by Xuanzang]. Indogaku Bukkyōgaku kenkyū \u003cem\u003e印度學佛教學研究 \u003c/em\u003e64 (2015): 499–92. Translated by Jeffrey Kotyk.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"ca298680-254f-47a1-b6c5-90cedde071cc\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eKotyk, Jeffrey. “Chinese State and Buddhist Historical Sources on Xuanzang: Historicity and the Daci’en si sanzang fashi zhuan 大慈恩寺三藏法師傳.” \u003cem\u003eT’oung Pao\u003c/em\u003e 105 (2019): 513–44. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"5351c372-67b9-421b-85f0-2a2a838b9709\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eLopez, Donald S. \u003cem\u003eElaborations on Emptiness: Uses of the Heart Sūtra\u003c/em\u003e. Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1996.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"0e4c59a6-29f6-47a8-9d7c-141031972cc8\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eLusthaus, Dan. “The Heart Sūtra in Chinese Yogācāra: Some Comparative Comments on the Heart Sūtra Commentaries of Wŏnch’ŭk and K’uei-chi.” \u003cem\u003eInternational Journal of Buddhist Thought and Culture\u003c/em\u003e 3 (2003): 59–103.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"50f6054b-40ee-47df-b27d-91ad751e8227\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNālandā Translation Committee. \u003cem\u003eThe Sūtra of the Heart of Transcendent Knowledge\u003c/em\u003e. 1980. Online publication. \u003ca href=\\\"https://www.nalandatranslation.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Heart-Sutra-for-website.pdf\\\"\u003ehttps://www.nalandatranslation.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Heart-Sutra-for-website.pdf\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"c56cff17-7d5c-464c-a836-150def762f92\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNattier, Jan. “The Heart Sūtra: A Chinese Apocryphal Text?” \u003cem\u003eJournal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies\u003c/em\u003e 15, no. 2 (1992): 153–223.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"17f260f8-8f7d-493d-8db1-7e3b719dd3b8\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003ePadmakara Translation Group, trans. \u003cem\u003e \u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh9.html\\\"\u003eThe Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-five Thousand Lines\u003c/a\u003e \u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003ePañca­viṃśati­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā\u003c/em\u003e, Toh 9). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2023.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"83ddd462-3809-46b8-aa9d-f51528884cc6\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSilk, Jonathan. \u003cem\u003eThe Heart Sutra in Tibetan: A Critical Edition of the Two Recensions Contained in the Kanjur\u003c/em\u003e. Wiener Studien zur Tibetologie und Buddhismuskunde, vol. 34. Vienna: Arbeitskreis fur Tibetische und Buddhistische Studien, Universitat Wien, 1994. \u003ca href=\\\"https://openphilology.eu/media/pages/publications-jonathan-silk/3568398551-1639738170/authored_1994_heart.pdf\\\"\u003ehttps://openphilology.eu/media/pages/publications-jonathan-silk/3568398551-1639738170/authored_1994_heart.pdf\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"a2c5beab-105f-4412-b2b9-96eba521e8ac\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSparham, Gareth (2021). “The Heart Sūtra as Dhāraṇī.” \u003cem\u003eActa Asiatica\u003c/em\u003e 121 (2021): 99–125.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"db761452-91db-4215-9e1b-6b73339892d0\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSparham, Gareth, trans. (2022). \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh10.html\\\"\u003eThe Transcendent Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eAṣṭa­daśa­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā\u003c/em\u003e, Toh 10). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2022.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"e1dd7890-0258-42f0-a7aa-a8cbcab6e2c0\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSparham, Gareth, trans. (2024). \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh8.html\\\"\u003eThe Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand Lines\u003c/a\u003e \u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eŚata­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā\u003c/em\u003e, Toh 8). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2024.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]}],\"endnotes\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"efb3e81e-235b-42e9-92ea-54b24b5a7348\",\"sort\":406,\"type\":\"endnotesHeader\",\"label\":\"n.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":5,\"uuid\":\"cd31bf1f-d497-4e15-919b-4c7e178d7f5c\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Notes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"76ce43be-d5be-423a-9e2a-d08100ae234a\",\"sort\":408,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.1\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother, which today is popularly known simply as The Heart Sūtra, has been cherished, read, and recited by Mahāyāna Buddhists in East and Central Asia for well over a millennium. Over the centuries, scholars and practitioners have continued to find deep meaning in this short scripture and vigorously debated its purpose and practice‍—and even whether to classify it as a sūtra or a tantra. Still today, The Heart Sūtra continues to be recited around the world in monasteries, temples, and meditation centers in a variety of Buddhist traditions. As a result of its popularity, in more recent times the sūtra has been translated into a wide variety of modern languages that are available in print and online.\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"sort\":27,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"bbaae9e8-5512-44df-9eb5-a5c1c08fdef5\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-6\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":462,\"uuid\":\"76ce43be-d5be-423a-9e2a-d08100ae234a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The title given in Stok (our representative of Recension B, as explained below) is \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":83}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Noble Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":126},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"168fbc7c-1f90-462a-bd52-014ca739cb53\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":128}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phags pa shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":182},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4737c8f3-0fd0-4acd-a971-8788f1751c9a\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":182,\"end\":184}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ārya­prajñā­pāramitā­hṛdaya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":184,\"end\":211},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ef681ffb-0350-47fb-9349-e566b17eb35b\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). However, the title that is included at the end of the text in Stok is \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":211,\"end\":284}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Noble Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":284,\"end\":347},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"18c29e8a-f34f-449a-8492-811bbbe49cdb\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":347,\"end\":349}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phags pa bcom ldan ’das ma shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":349,\"end\":421},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bb0a86f0-2a3c-416f-8169-66cc8b1b19c2\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":421,\"end\":423}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ārya­bhagavatī­prajñā­pāramitā­hṛdaya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":423,\"end\":460},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4cafdddc-445e-4c82-9d30-40d758600e57\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":460,\"end\":462}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3bb043f8-7c8e-4662-85b6-3486e8fed258\",\"sort\":422,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.2\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother, which today is popularly known simply as The Heart Sūtra, has been cherished, read, and recited by Mahāyāna Buddhists in East and Central Asia for well over a millennium. Over the centuries, scholars and practitioners have continued to find deep meaning in this short scripture and vigorously debated its purpose and practice‍—and even whether to classify it as a sūtra or a tantra. Still today, The Heart Sūtra continues to be recited around the world in monasteries, temples, and meditation centers in a variety of Buddhist traditions. As a result of its popularity, in more recent times the sūtra has been translated into a wide variety of modern languages that are available in print and online.\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"sort\":27,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"bbaae9e8-5512-44df-9eb5-a5c1c08fdef5\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-6\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79,\"uuid\":\"3bb043f8-7c8e-4662-85b6-3486e8fed258\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1,\"end\":12},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bc4d7627-066b-440d-94dd-c7736b4ebb5c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” is a translation of the last two words of the Chinese title (心經).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":79}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bbfaa8a1-0236-41c5-a42f-f52128e7956a\",\"sort\":428,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.3\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The sūtra takes place on Vulture Peak Mountain near Rājagṛha. Here the Buddha inspires his senior monk Śāriputra to request instructions from the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara regarding the practice of the perfection of wisdom. Prompted in this way, Avalokiteśvara describes how an aspiring practitioner of the perfection of wisdom must first understand that all phenomena lack an intrinsic nature and therefore are empty. To manifest this realization in the practitioner, Avalokiteśvara reveals a brief mantra to be recited: tadyathā gate gate pāragate pārasaṃgate bodhi svāhā. Following Avalokiteśvara’s teaching, the Buddha offers his endorsement of what has been said and confirms that this is indeed the foremost way to practice the perfection of wisdom.\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"f325aa67-f947-49bf-8d77-4d6f57d00775\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":213,\"uuid\":\"bbfaa8a1-0236-41c5-a42f-f52128e7956a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In Prajñāpāramitā literature in general, the presence of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":71},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"562160a5-ad45-437e-b224-311b9e72302f\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as an interlocutor is unique to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":104}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":104,\"end\":119},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2549928e-30bd-4aba-8f93-98bcf2ee1fe0\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Usually, this role is performed by other disciples of the Buddha, such as the elder Subhūti.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":119,\"end\":213}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"14105497-864a-46a2-a6bb-a711c4ad495c\",\"sort\":434,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.4\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$20\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":65,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1866,\"uuid\":\"14105497-864a-46a2-a6bb-a711c4ad495c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"998584a3-78fe-4a0c-af9e-b77f08d7a9aa\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s Chinese origins were first pointed out in English by Jan Nattier (1992), who argued that the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":15,\"end\":128}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":143},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3f5c9d62-c56d-4982-b689-c2b42d30a3b9\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was originally compiled in China rather than India. Nattier further suggested that \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":143,\"end\":227}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":227,\"end\":242},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"421749f9-2ffc-4b8f-bfe6-5a2f4188e487\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was transmitted to the famous Chinese translator Xuanzang (600/602–64), who edited the Chinese text and subsequently translated it into Sanskrit. Some elements in Nattier’s study, such as the role of Xuanzang in producing the Sanskrit translation and subsequently transmitting the sūtra within China, have since been challenged by other scholars, such as Dan Lusthaus (2003, pp. 81–87) and Kōsei Ishii (2015). For a critique of Lusthaus’s arguments, see Attwood 2020. Jeffrey Kotyk (2019, pp. 538–40) also argues that Xuanzang is unlikely to have received \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":242,\"end\":799}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":799,\"end\":814},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"33a779b5-8e22-4e06-a689-6b637ea74d4e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" prior to his journey to India but suggests that he may have compiled it in Chinese after his return to China. Nevertheless, Nattier’s main thesis‍—that the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":814,\"end\":988}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":988,\"end\":1003},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"00191e58-9c08-4d19-9058-966950b949a6\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was originally compiled in China based on existing sources in Chinese‍—still appears the most compelling account of events. Notably, Shi (2014) was the first scholar to apply Nattier’s methods to other parts of the text. Over the last decade, Jayarava Attwood has written extensively on this topic (e.g., 2015, 2017a, 2017b, 2018, 2019, 2020, and 2021) and provided many new insights in favor of the Chinese origin of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1003,\"end\":1422}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1422,\"end\":1437},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bea3319b-894f-44ae-af14-b70aedc6ca7b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Besides adding weight to the argument that the sūtra was compiled in China, Attwood’s writings have also contributed much to our general knowledge of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1437,\"end\":1589}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1589,\"end\":1604},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"35ad7ebd-d860-48a6-9e34-310a3dfd88e6\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", in particular the history and linguistic nature of the Chinese and Sanskrit sources. Besides the articles by Attwood included in this bibliography, links to his other published articles on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1604,\"end\":1795}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1795,\"end\":1810},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b03bcd52-3ba8-4380-94da-6ac4f8e2c031\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" can be found at his blog: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1810,\"end\":1837}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"http://jayarava.blogspot.com\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1837,\"end\":1865},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"link\",\"attrs\":{\"href\":\"http://jayarava.blogspot.com\",\"uuid\":\"975754b9-c46a-4bb9-9dcf-29e2e2af22ad\",\"type\":\"link\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1865,\"end\":1866}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"96186a0e-8e29-45a6-a6fc-cce5c0cfa5ea\",\"sort\":455,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.5\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$21\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":65,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":376,\"uuid\":\"179e49ce-06a9-4c8a-ab83-f4324f83aeed\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This mantra was most likely extracted from the Chinese translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dhāraṇī­samuccaya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":91},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"04217daa-5f55-4c51-8f6a-c8f249ba0264\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Taishō 901), which was translated into Chinese in 654 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":147}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":147,\"end\":149},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":147,\"end\":149,\"uuid\":\"f1a5467b-157d-4f21-bdaa-2920e815caf8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". This possibility was already mentioned by Nattier, but without providing any details (1992, p. 177). The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":256}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dhāraṇī­samuccaya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":256,\"end\":273},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"62a0669b-69c3-41b9-b843-3499f89a2c19\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" does indeed contain the mantra that is included in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":273,\"end\":325}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":325,\"end\":340},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"88d01232-dc19-43c8-b19a-2650531fe86b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the passage in question reads: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":340,\"end\":376}}]},{\"type\":\"lineGroup\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":376,\"end\":876,\"uuid\":\"7f280ce9-a8fa-4d8b-8584-e11f703bbaee\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“16. The Great Heart Dhāraṇī of Prajñāpāramitā \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":376,\"end\":423}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":376,\"end\":423,\"uuid\":\"94d1da73-cbf8-476b-b11b-47c74e6799c2\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The incantation goes: Duozhita (1). Jiedi jiedi (2). Boluo jiedi (3). Boluoseng jiedi (4). Puti (5). Shahe (6). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":423,\"end\":535}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":423,\"end\":535,\"uuid\":\"a702b7a2-4c69-4546-981f-ffb7ef9d699b\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For this great heart incantation, use the Great Heart Seal. It can be used comprehensively with all the various altars [i.e., for all different ritual applications]. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":535,\"end\":701}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":535,\"end\":701,\"uuid\":\"b4d28b9d-3c2e-4aa7-83ae-7987250f0c22\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Lesser Heart Dhāraṇī of Prajñāpāramitā goes: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":701,\"end\":750}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":701,\"end\":750,\"uuid\":\"3b34a710-5214-4a96-95a9-5c380c4b6ec4\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Duozhita (1). Jiedi jiedi (2). Boluomin jiedi (3). Boluoreta (4). Shahe (5). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":750,\"end\":827}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":750,\"end\":827,\"uuid\":\"47a8a79c-cf4d-42dc-83d4-ac8f211351f3\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Use the Lesser Heart Seal for all applications.” \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":827,\"end\":876}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":827,\"end\":876,\"uuid\":\"70f4ac0b-5fd0-42f8-bd13-ed87ca7affdf\"}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":876,\"end\":894,\"uuid\":\"f466a9a2-8e42-4403-80da-f92aecadd031\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Chinese reads:\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":876,\"end\":894}}]},{\"type\":\"lineGroup\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":894,\"end\":1055,\"uuid\":\"c9e4154b-0e98-4b25-8384-438555fbb75d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"《陀羅尼集經》卷〈佛說跋折囉功能法相品〉般若大心陀羅尼第十六　呪曰。 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":894,\"end\":929}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":894,\"end\":929,\"uuid\":\"5dce8720-e1d9-4cfb-b7e2-81d85c472d0c\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"跢姪他(一)揭帝揭帝(二)波羅揭帝(三)波囉僧揭 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":929,\"end\":954}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":929,\"end\":954,\"uuid\":\"b201e3ef-278f-4c25-bb15-24afd135ac00\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"帝(四)菩提(五)莎訶(六) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":954,\"end\":969}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":954,\"end\":969,\"uuid\":\"ee9d2e5c-3f55-48b3-8639-975edd6a27ad\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"是大心呪。用大心印。作諸壇處一切通用。 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":969,\"end\":989}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":969,\"end\":989,\"uuid\":\"0d47df1d-0ac7-4981-bf9f-4a8c47df81fc\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"般若小心陀羅尼呪曰。 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":989,\"end\":1000}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":989,\"end\":1000,\"uuid\":\"30937f97-99b4-4055-8ae8-39e6807befc1\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"跢姪他(一)揭帝揭帝(二)波囉民(彌忍反)揭帝(三)波 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1000,\"end\":1028}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1000,\"end\":1028,\"uuid\":\"a027ee6c-f95b-49a2-b728-b5ea5e9fd03e\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"囉若(若冶反)他(四)莎訶(五) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1028,\"end\":1045}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1028,\"end\":1045,\"uuid\":\"5d6b06db-2b5c-46d4-9153-b16d498deed2\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"用小心印通一切用。 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1045,\"end\":1055}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1045,\"end\":1055,\"uuid\":\"250dd0df-1854-4626-bf57-e24d56ffb72a\"}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1055,\"end\":1144,\"uuid\":\"0e39ce15-1a2f-45d6-8bb0-d1d238bc40fa\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(CBETA, T18, no. 901, p. 807, b19–26. The incantation itself is found at 18: 807b20–21.) \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1055,\"end\":1144}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1144,\"end\":1596,\"uuid\":\"c64967af-f1ea-4c9e-8a9a-f3b83c8a9eda\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Interestingly, Taishō 901 includes \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1144,\"end\":1179}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tadyathā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1179,\"end\":1187},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1179,\"end\":1187,\"uuid\":\"2383a40a-d581-4e69-98e8-f98976812802\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1187,\"end\":1189}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"duozhita\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1189,\"end\":1197},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1189,\"end\":1197,\"uuid\":\"6486203c-c1f0-4d34-ab29-e60c77101889\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") at the beginning of the incantation, as do the Sanskrit and Tibetan versions, whereas this is not found in the Chinese versions of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1197,\"end\":1330}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1330,\"end\":1345},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"77b04355-c860-4785-9fe5-ed55b1ab6ac2\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". There are a few additional incantations in this section of Taishō 901 that are also labeled “heart dhāraṇī” or “lesser heart dhāraṇī.” We are grateful to Josh Capitanio for locating this passage in Taishō 901 and for providing the above translation.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1345,\"end\":1596}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"359bc88a-cac1-4651-86d4-6cfc9fea8e8b\",\"sort\":502,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.6\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$22\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":65,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":59,\"uuid\":\"359bc88a-cac1-4651-86d4-6cfc9fea8e8b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Attwood 2020, pp. 161–64. See also Attwood 2019, pp. 19–23.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":59}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1e485bb7-ba1f-4f8d-95d6-35c1844333de\",\"sort\":504,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.7\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$23\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":65,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":111,\"uuid\":\"1e485bb7-ba1f-4f8d-95d6-35c1844333de\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The actual term used in this sūtra is \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":38}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pratibhāna\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"6c5817e7-bdda-4eef-b272-3bb6a840cd0f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"spobs pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":58},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"9b96e09b-0d15-48c9-ae86-7e6c5c7dfcf7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), which can also be translated as “inspired speech”.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":111}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ace0454d-3ac7-4437-ac2e-388d77808253\",\"sort\":510,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.8\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$24\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"sort\":65,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":134,\"uuid\":\"ace0454d-3ac7-4437-ac2e-388d77808253\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See Blazing Wisdom Translation Group, trans., \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":46}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Inspiring Determination\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":69},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"148bbea5-67cb-454e-a9d6-bb215d2f9de5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":46,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c9dd70e-1c81-4fed-a6f0-179d495c5189\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/f3653c32-d091-4ed5-b9e1-a67c6fb0379f\",\"entity\":\"f3653c32-d091-4ed5-b9e1-a67c6fb0379f\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"subtype\":\"translation\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 69 (84000:Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2021), 1.80.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":134}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8779a750-1c7d-4367-8b42-f64ada1c7473\",\"sort\":514,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.9\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Traditionally, the earliest version of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese was thought to be Taishō 250, which in traditional sources is described as a translation of Kumārajīva. However, this attribution is generally no longer accepted, and some scholars have placed it later in time‍—some even in the beginning of the eighth century ᴄᴇ. Apart from Taishō 250, the earliest witness for The Heart Sūtra’s existence is a famous stone stele, which was discovered in the early twentieth century at the Yunju Temple in the Fangshan region near Beijing. The inscription on this stele is a rendering of the short version of The Heart Sūtra, and the colophon is dated to 661. The colophon further states that this is the translation prepared by Xuanzang (i.e., an equivalent of Taishō 251). Of the three shorter versions of the text in Chinese, this is the one that has been commonly read and recited across East Asia down to the present day.\",\"label\":\"i.5\",\"sort\":105,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"3441b1f0-e501-499c-8c80-d7176aa83af9\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-19\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":115,\"uuid\":\"8779a750-1c7d-4367-8b42-f64ada1c7473\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For arguments in favor of and against an early dating of this text, see Lusthaus 2003 (pp. 86–87) and Attwood 2020.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":115}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"84225b71-239c-4976-aec6-10e347f90c1c\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.10\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Traditionally, the earliest version of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese was thought to be Taishō 250, which in traditional sources is described as a translation of Kumārajīva. However, this attribution is generally no longer accepted, and some scholars have placed it later in time‍—some even in the beginning of the eighth century ᴄᴇ. Apart from Taishō 250, the earliest witness for The Heart Sūtra’s existence is a famous stone stele, which was discovered in the early twentieth century at the Yunju Temple in the Fangshan region near Beijing. The inscription on this stele is a rendering of the short version of The Heart Sūtra, and the colophon is dated to 661. The colophon further states that this is the translation prepared by Xuanzang (i.e., an equivalent of Taishō 251). Of the three shorter versions of the text in Chinese, this is the one that has been commonly read and recited across East Asia down to the present day.\",\"label\":\"i.5\",\"sort\":105,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"3441b1f0-e501-499c-8c80-d7176aa83af9\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-19\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":252,\"uuid\":\"84225b71-239c-4976-aec6-10e347f90c1c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In spite of the colophon’s claim, we now know that Xuanzang could not have translated the sūtra into Chinese, since it was rather translated \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":141}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"from\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":141,\"end\":145},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":141,\"end\":145,\"uuid\":\"9fab4250-638b-4acb-b68a-8c16469cc20b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"emphasis\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Chinese into Sanskrit subsequent to its appearance in China. See Attwood 2019 and Kotyk 2019 (pp. 538–40).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":145,\"end\":252}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"75b76cfd-ba35-46ea-9d3c-15447ea9ffac\",\"sort\":520,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.11\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Traditionally, the earliest version of The Heart Sūtra in Chinese was thought to be Taishō 250, which in traditional sources is described as a translation of Kumārajīva. However, this attribution is generally no longer accepted, and some scholars have placed it later in time‍—some even in the beginning of the eighth century ᴄᴇ. Apart from Taishō 250, the earliest witness for The Heart Sūtra’s existence is a famous stone stele, which was discovered in the early twentieth century at the Yunju Temple in the Fangshan region near Beijing. The inscription on this stele is a rendering of the short version of The Heart Sūtra, and the colophon is dated to 661. The colophon further states that this is the translation prepared by Xuanzang (i.e., an equivalent of Taishō 251). Of the three shorter versions of the text in Chinese, this is the one that has been commonly read and recited across East Asia down to the present day.\",\"label\":\"i.5\",\"sort\":105,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"3441b1f0-e501-499c-8c80-d7176aa83af9\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-19\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":171,\"uuid\":\"75b76cfd-ba35-46ea-9d3c-15447ea9ffac\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Besides Taishō 250 and Taishō 251, there is one additional version of the short sūtra: Taishō 256. However, this version is a transliteration into Chinese of the Sanskrit.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":171}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e26f6b3b-134a-4aec-9e6b-e69c66ee49df\",\"sort\":522,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.12\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$25\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":121,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"14033cbc-7c26-463e-99b1-be8164150c5d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-23\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"e26f6b3b-134a-4aec-9e6b-e69c66ee49df\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Silk 2021, p. 103.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"61214501-32a6-4883-8d04-81042874777d\",\"sort\":524,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.13\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$26\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":121,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"14033cbc-7c26-463e-99b1-be8164150c5d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-23\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":187,\"uuid\":\"61214501-32a6-4883-8d04-81042874777d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"On the Sanskrit manuscripts, see Conze 1967. Many edited versions of the Sanskrit text have also been published over the last century. For a listing of these, see Attwood 2015, pp. 45–46.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":187}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d18f74d1-ccbb-4cef-9494-dd880c8d2bac\",\"sort\":526,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.14\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$27\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":121,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"14033cbc-7c26-463e-99b1-be8164150c5d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-23\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":157,\"uuid\":\"d18f74d1-ccbb-4cef-9494-dd880c8d2bac\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Previously, scholars had dated this manuscript to 609 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":56},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":56,\"uuid\":\"d6a53c19-ca5b-4f5a-bb2d-4bb3c4bb4ded\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", but this dating was not accurate. See Silk 2021, pp. 102–4. See also Attwood 2015, p. 30 (and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":152}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.6\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":152,\"end\":155},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0b546ea5-1e06-416a-b21f-57557109e164\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/359bc88a-cac1-4651-86d4-6cfc9fea8e8b\",\"entity\":\"359bc88a-cac1-4651-86d4-6cfc9fea8e8b\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":155,\"end\":157}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1e4a46d9-68ae-429a-8a9e-4a644aadfc3f\",\"sort\":532,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.15\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$28\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":121,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"14033cbc-7c26-463e-99b1-be8164150c5d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-23\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":876,\"uuid\":\"1e4a46d9-68ae-429a-8a9e-4a644aadfc3f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"On the Tibetan translations of the shorter version, see Attwood 2015, pp. 38–40. Interestingly, in addition to the Tibetan translations found at Dunhuang, one manuscript (Pelliot tibétain 448) consists of a transliteration into Tibetan of the Chinese text (a scan of this manuscript can be viewed at: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":301}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b83061587\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":301,\"end\":348},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"link\",\"attrs\":{\"href\":\"https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b83061587\",\"uuid\":\"ee2d14af-b181-49f7-bdee-947478a52428\",\"type\":\"link\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). This manuscript appears to have been produced for recitation of the Chinese text by those Tibetans in the region who could not read the Chinese characters. This could perhaps indicate that the Chinese version enjoyed a privileged status compared to the Tibetan translation, even by those who could only read Tibetan. For a scan of a Dunhuang manuscript with Tibetan translation of the short version, currently held at the British Library (Or. 8212/77), see: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":348,\"end\":809}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"http://idp.bl.uk/database/large.a4d?recnum=7852\u0026imageRecnum=122101\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":809,\"end\":875},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"link\",\"attrs\":{\"href\":\"http://idp.bl.uk/database/large.a4d?recnum=7852\u0026imageRecnum=122101\",\"uuid\":\"1559613e-e38d-4cbe-91a0-09c193ab21f8\",\"type\":\"link\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":875,\"end\":876}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"da13e7fc-2763-45be-a004-2e6226787809\",\"sort\":538,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.16\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$29\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":134,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"cb948a05-93b4-4b7a-8037-7535b06d8f1d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-28\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"da13e7fc-2763-45be-a004-2e6226787809\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Attwood 2019, pp. 25–26.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b44679ad-cae1-45bf-8636-e822bf3c6d3a\",\"sort\":540,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.17\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2a\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":134,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"cb948a05-93b4-4b7a-8037-7535b06d8f1d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-28\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":8,\"uuid\":\"b44679ad-cae1-45bf-8636-e822bf3c6d3a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.5\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":7},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1b513cb5-318e-4444-94b9-3c746d9e82cd\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/96186a0e-8e29-45a6-a6fc-cce5c0cfa5ea\",\"entity\":\"96186a0e-8e29-45a6-a6fc-cce5c0cfa5ea\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":8}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"08049e5d-d7eb-4604-af4a-e0619a05c5d4\",\"sort\":544,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.18\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2b\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":134,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"cb948a05-93b4-4b7a-8037-7535b06d8f1d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-28\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79,\"uuid\":\"08049e5d-d7eb-4604-af4a-e0619a05c5d4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This time of compilation has been suggested by Jeffrey Kotyk (2019, p. 538–40).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6c9a404a-a7ef-47f4-9225-5f0819760cba\",\"sort\":546,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.19\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The earliest version of the long sūtra, traditionally dated to 738 ᴄᴇ, is a text that only exists in Chinese (Taishō 252). While the text presents itself as a translation from Sanskrit, it is most likely an early attempt to present the short sūtra in a traditional literary format by adding an introduction and a concluding section, which appear to have been composed directly in Chinese. This version does not seem to have gained much popularity, as its unique introduction was never replicated or copied in other sources.\",\"label\":\"i.9\",\"sort\":164,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"3ae45e54-c0b9-43af-b9be-542c00e16e8f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-34\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":169,\"uuid\":\"6c9a404a-a7ef-47f4-9225-5f0819760cba\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For a detailed comparison of the five Chinese versions of the longer sūtra (Taishō 252, 253, 254, 255, and 257), see Attwood 2021. See also Nattier 1992, p. 200, note 1.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":169}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0bd9663f-cd0d-47d4-bd94-f9383154361f\",\"sort\":548,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.20\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The four remaining Chinese versions of the long sūtra (Taishō 253, 254, 255, and 257) are all translations that were produced either from Sanskrit or Tibetan manuscripts. Although they each feature certain idiosyncratic elements, all of them clearly belong to the same family in text-historical terms. Unfortunately, there are no surviving Sanskrit manuscripts from the period when these four translations were produced, from the late eighth to the early eleventh century. The earliest Sanskrit witnesses we have of the longer version of The Heart Sūtra are Nepalese manuscripts that were produced several centuries later.\",\"label\":\"i.10\",\"sort\":169,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab0fab66-d4f5-4523-b609-c8afdfcabaf2\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-36\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":94,\"uuid\":\"0bd9663f-cd0d-47d4-bd94-f9383154361f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Of these, Taishō 253, 254, and 257 were translated from Sanskrit, and Taishō 255 from Tibetan.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":94}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b1441bbb-3d26-4a1c-b5b8-338ef397c375\",\"sort\":550,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.21\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The four remaining Chinese versions of the long sūtra (Taishō 253, 254, 255, and 257) are all translations that were produced either from Sanskrit or Tibetan manuscripts. Although they each feature certain idiosyncratic elements, all of them clearly belong to the same family in text-historical terms. Unfortunately, there are no surviving Sanskrit manuscripts from the period when these four translations were produced, from the late eighth to the early eleventh century. The earliest Sanskrit witnesses we have of the longer version of The Heart Sūtra are Nepalese manuscripts that were produced several centuries later.\",\"label\":\"i.10\",\"sort\":169,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"ab0fab66-d4f5-4523-b609-c8afdfcabaf2\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-36\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":236,\"uuid\":\"b1441bbb-3d26-4a1c-b5b8-338ef397c375\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Taishō 253 was translated in 788 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":35},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":35,\"uuid\":\"c09c6fb5-8f8c-489b-b3d7-89cd0e206a1d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Taishō 254 in 861 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"1a221df1-36a8-44ba-b51e-8a643702f397\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and Taishō 257 in 1005 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":82}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":82,\"end\":84},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":82,\"end\":84,\"uuid\":\"c62091e3-16b1-4fa4-873a-c151529f1772\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Taishō 255 was translated from Tibetan in 856. On these dates see Attwood 2015, p. 38. Note, however, that these dates still require further research.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":236}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"03adccb4-b20b-4d29-9eb4-edb306398468\",\"sort\":558,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.22\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Just as with the Sanskrit translation of the short sūtra, we also do not know the circumstances in which the Sanskrit text of the longer version first appeared. It must have taken place, however, prior to 788 ᴄᴇ, when the first Chinese translation from Sanskrit was produced. At around the same time, the two Tibetan translations, which were subsequently included in the Kangyur (see more below), must also have been produced. We can say that with some confidence, since the translation is recorded in the Denkarma catalog of completed translations, which is dated to 812.\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"sort\":179,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"29046a65-a333-4fee-a3af-501e04eb0394\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-39\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":80,\"uuid\":\"03adccb4-b20b-4d29-9eb4-edb306398468\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See Denkarma, folio 295.a.6. See also Herrmann-Pfandt 2008, pp. 9–10, number 14.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":80}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5bc1b348-9861-43f3-9799-5ecdec2cd745\",\"sort\":560,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.23\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In the Tengyur collections seven commentaries on the long sūtra by Indian scholars and one by a Chinese scholar are included in Tibetan translation. Some of these commentaries were composed by such well-known names in Tibetan history as Kamalaśīla (740–95), Vimalamitra (eighth/ninth c.), and Atīśa (982–1054). The authors of these commentaries were all active from the eighth to the eleventh century and most of them are known to have visited Tibet. Interestingly, the different commentators view The Heart Sūtra through very diverse hermeneutical lenses and interpret it variously through the systems of sūtra, tantra, and even ritual practice (sādhana). This great variety of interpretations, combined with the fact that there is no mention of The Heart Sūtra in any other source linked to India, makes it seem likely that the commentaries were all composed in Tibet during the sojourns of these Indian masters there.\",\"label\":\"i.12\",\"sort\":184,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"76fdeff3-d747-4f88-a127-fa6fae9ea0e0\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-41\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":352,\"uuid\":\"5bc1b348-9861-43f3-9799-5ecdec2cd745\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Seven of the commentaries are included in the Degé Tengyur (Toh 3818–3823, all in the Perfection of Wisdom section, and Toh 4353, in the Miscellaneous section). The eighth commentary is only included in the Peking (P 5221) and Narthang (3994) Tengyurs. All eight commentaries have been translated into English and commented upon by Donald Lopez (1996).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":352}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"dc18655b-e514-4b3f-a58f-b4e8453e77bf\",\"sort\":562,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.24\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In the Tengyur collections seven commentaries on the long sūtra by Indian scholars and one by a Chinese scholar are included in Tibetan translation. Some of these commentaries were composed by such well-known names in Tibetan history as Kamalaśīla (740–95), Vimalamitra (eighth/ninth c.), and Atīśa (982–1054). The authors of these commentaries were all active from the eighth to the eleventh century and most of them are known to have visited Tibet. Interestingly, the different commentators view The Heart Sūtra through very diverse hermeneutical lenses and interpret it variously through the systems of sūtra, tantra, and even ritual practice (sādhana). This great variety of interpretations, combined with the fact that there is no mention of The Heart Sūtra in any other source linked to India, makes it seem likely that the commentaries were all composed in Tibet during the sojourns of these Indian masters there.\",\"label\":\"i.12\",\"sort\":184,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"76fdeff3-d747-4f88-a127-fa6fae9ea0e0\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-41\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":468,\"uuid\":\"dc18655b-e514-4b3f-a58f-b4e8453e77bf\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"We know that Kamalaśīla, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vimalamitra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":36},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a\",\"uuid\":\"6a21a6e6-3bff-422d-af68-fa2bb0a46f57\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Atīśa, Vajrapāṇi (eleventh century), and Mahājana (eleventh century) all visited Tibet. Moreover, according to Toshio Horiuchi (2021), at least the two commentaries by Śrīsiṃha (dates uncertain) and Jñānamitra (dates uncertain) were composed directly in Tibetan. As for Praśāstrasena (dates uncertain), we do not have any biographical details, so it is not clear whether he ever visited Tibet or where his commentary was composed.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":36,\"end\":468}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bb5cc842-1bc6-4198-aa59-79b6e76a757c\",\"sort\":566,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.25\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$2c\",\"label\":\"i.13\",\"sort\":197,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"0b78f0d6-1373-464c-abbd-9085ff8147f2\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-44\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"bb5cc842-1bc6-4198-aa59-79b6e76a757c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Attwood 2021, p. 63.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"978942c1-69bd-4548-98c0-cd7653a821a7\",\"sort\":568,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.26\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In Tibet, only the longer version of The Heart Sūtra was included in the various Kangyur collections, where it has been preserved in two recensions, which Jonathan Silk has designated Recension A and Recension B. These two recensions represent individual manuscript traditions and appear to have been translated into Tibetan by different translators, although the exact details remain unknown. The two recensions vary on several significant points, such as the title of the text, the name of the absorption in which the Buddha rests, the mantra that Avalokiteśvara reveals, and the presence or absence of a translator’s colophon.\",\"label\":\"i.14\",\"sort\":205,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"23578ae0-738f-47be-a5fd-ad38ab804a1a\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-47\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":51,\"uuid\":\"978942c1-69bd-4548-98c0-cd7653a821a7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See Silk 1994 for editions of these two recensions.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":51}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c4c71011-bb00-4dc2-98ec-b484b8cda947\",\"sort\":570,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.27\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"In Tibet, only the longer version of The Heart Sūtra was included in the various Kangyur collections, where it has been preserved in two recensions, which Jonathan Silk has designated Recension A and Recension B. These two recensions represent individual manuscript traditions and appear to have been translated into Tibetan by different translators, although the exact details remain unknown. The two recensions vary on several significant points, such as the title of the text, the name of the absorption in which the Buddha rests, the mantra that Avalokiteśvara reveals, and the presence or absence of a translator’s colophon.\",\"label\":\"i.14\",\"sort\":205,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"23578ae0-738f-47be-a5fd-ad38ab804a1a\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-47\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":237,\"uuid\":\"c4c71011-bb00-4dc2-98ec-b484b8cda947\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Recension A, which we have translated here, contains a translators’ colophon specifying that the translation was produced by the Indian scholar \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":144}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vimalamitra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":144,\"end\":155},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a\",\"uuid\":\"23752ea8-13f2-4aa2-9ab9-3bc041b354ef\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the Tibetan translator \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":155,\"end\":183}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Dé\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":183,\"end\":193},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b3a43e78-559c-44a4-a203-e14d6ee55eac\",\"uuid\":\"437fbf29-2af0-426a-997e-cb06e2829daa\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Recension B lacks a translators’ colophon.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":193,\"end\":237}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"325699cb-d7e1-4e0a-a96d-8c39ebf6facc\",\"sort\":576,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.28\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The fact that The Heart Sūtra incorporates elements of both sūtra and tantra, and therefore has been variously classified throughout its history, is evident from its placement in the different Kangyur collections, where it often appears twice in both the Tantra section and the Perfection of Wisdom section. Generally speaking, all Kangyurs include Recension A in their Tantra sections, whereas some Kangyurs, mostly those of the Thempangma (them spangs ma) branch, also include Recension B in the Perfection of Wisdom section. The Kangyurs that belong to the Tshalpa (tshal pa) branch mostly include the text only once, in the Tantra section. In the Degé Kangyur, however, the text appears in both the Perfection of Wisdom and the Tantra sections, but, unlike the Thempangma Kangyurs, the Degé Kangyur includes Recension A both times, thus omitting Recension B.\",\"label\":\"i.15\",\"sort\":215,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"eb16cd74-fa4c-4c7d-839d-dc65be86ea7f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-50\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":237,\"uuid\":\"325699cb-d7e1-4e0a-a96d-8c39ebf6facc\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Within the Perfection of Wisdom section, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":56},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b0e97c89-ec79-40b4-867d-8ae39961055d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is placed in a final volume of miscellaneous Perfection of Wisdom scriptures (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":135}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sher phyin sna tshogs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":135,\"end\":156},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":135,\"end\":156,\"uuid\":\"0fd39b3c-9390-47b4-87dd-f23cff293cc2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). On \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":156,\"end\":162}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":162,\"end\":177},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c8a167c7-f905-49dd-9f98-0c971e41c7be\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" being classified (and practiced) as dhāraṇī, see Silk 2021.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":177,\"end\":237}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"57060c94-2672-4be3-9989-e17fa2b7a512\",\"sort\":584,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.29\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The fact that The Heart Sūtra incorporates elements of both sūtra and tantra, and therefore has been variously classified throughout its history, is evident from its placement in the different Kangyur collections, where it often appears twice in both the Tantra section and the Perfection of Wisdom section. Generally speaking, all Kangyurs include Recension A in their Tantra sections, whereas some Kangyurs, mostly those of the Thempangma (them spangs ma) branch, also include Recension B in the Perfection of Wisdom section. The Kangyurs that belong to the Tshalpa (tshal pa) branch mostly include the text only once, in the Tantra section. In the Degé Kangyur, however, the text appears in both the Perfection of Wisdom and the Tantra sections, but, unlike the Thempangma Kangyurs, the Degé Kangyur includes Recension A both times, thus omitting Recension B.\",\"label\":\"i.15\",\"sort\":215,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"eb16cd74-fa4c-4c7d-839d-dc65be86ea7f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-50\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":109,\"uuid\":\"57060c94-2672-4be3-9989-e17fa2b7a512\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Besides the Thempangma Kangyurs, Narthang (from the “mixed” group of Kangyurs) also includes both recensions.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":109}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ef709bb1-0d32-4f67-9032-10e6c597acba\",\"sort\":586,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.30\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The fact that The Heart Sūtra incorporates elements of both sūtra and tantra, and therefore has been variously classified throughout its history, is evident from its placement in the different Kangyur collections, where it often appears twice in both the Tantra section and the Perfection of Wisdom section. Generally speaking, all Kangyurs include Recension A in their Tantra sections, whereas some Kangyurs, mostly those of the Thempangma (them spangs ma) branch, also include Recension B in the Perfection of Wisdom section. The Kangyurs that belong to the Tshalpa (tshal pa) branch mostly include the text only once, in the Tantra section. In the Degé Kangyur, however, the text appears in both the Perfection of Wisdom and the Tantra sections, but, unlike the Thempangma Kangyurs, the Degé Kangyur includes Recension A both times, thus omitting Recension B.\",\"label\":\"i.15\",\"sort\":215,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"eb16cd74-fa4c-4c7d-839d-dc65be86ea7f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-50\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":84,\"uuid\":\"ef709bb1-0d32-4f67-9032-10e6c597acba\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This is the case with the Berlin, Choné, Lithang, Peking, Dragon, and Urga Kangyurs.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":84}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d8a2ead0-b089-4899-a452-f38f56f93f93\",\"sort\":588,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.31\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The fact that The Heart Sūtra incorporates elements of both sūtra and tantra, and therefore has been variously classified throughout its history, is evident from its placement in the different Kangyur collections, where it often appears twice in both the Tantra section and the Perfection of Wisdom section. Generally speaking, all Kangyurs include Recension A in their Tantra sections, whereas some Kangyurs, mostly those of the Thempangma (them spangs ma) branch, also include Recension B in the Perfection of Wisdom section. The Kangyurs that belong to the Tshalpa (tshal pa) branch mostly include the text only once, in the Tantra section. In the Degé Kangyur, however, the text appears in both the Perfection of Wisdom and the Tantra sections, but, unlike the Thempangma Kangyurs, the Degé Kangyur includes Recension A both times, thus omitting Recension B.\",\"label\":\"i.15\",\"sort\":215,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"eb16cd74-fa4c-4c7d-839d-dc65be86ea7f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-50\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":167,\"uuid\":\"d8a2ead0-b089-4899-a452-f38f56f93f93\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Besides the Degé Kangyur, Recension A is also included twice in the Ragya Kangyur. In the “mixed” group of Kangyurs, Lhasa and Phukdrak also include Recension A twice.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":167}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d6e5fd62-f62c-4989-8cf2-ffa3db620f6c\",\"sort\":590,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.32\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Our translation is based primarily on the version of Recension A that is included in the Degé Kangyur. We have made Recension A our primary focus in order to present in English one important version of The Heart Sūtra as it has been transmitted in Tibet since the early ninth century, rather than attempting to edit this version in search of an elusive urtext. However, to give the reader a taste of the differences between the two Tibetan recensions‍—differences that the Tibetans found worthy of preservation in their Kangyurs‍—we have included in the form of notes the most significant variations between the Degé text and the version of Recension B that is included in the Perfection of Wisdom section in the Stok Palace Kangyur. We have also attempted, whenever possible, to let our translation be informed by the published Sanskrit editions of The Heart Sūtra, the eight commentaries on the text in the Tengyur collections, and the growing scholarly literature on The Heart Sūtra.\",\"label\":\"i.16\",\"sort\":232,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"e7d3dc8c-ddd8-44b2-9455-1cb3bc80d253\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-55\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":377,\"uuid\":\"d6e5fd62-f62c-4989-8cf2-ffa3db620f6c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In our notes, “Stok” refers exclusively to this text of the Perfection of Wisdom section, since the other version of the text in the Stok Palace Kangyur belongs to Recension A. Besides the differences that we have noted here, there are numerous minor differences between the two recensions, even within the individual versions of the two recensions. For details, see Silk 1994.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":377}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4d1896b2-dcf3-4b01-8cc6-8bd5e30c9d67\",\"sort\":593,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.33\",\"toh\":\"toh21\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Homage to the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother! Thus did I hear at one time. The Blessed One was residing on Vulture Peak Mountain at Rājagṛha together with a great saṅgha of monks and a great saṅgha of bodhisattvas.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":251,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"900d66c8-caef-469f-911b-98cba686dcea\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-59\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":318,\"uuid\":\"4d1896b2-dcf3-4b01-8cc6-8bd5e30c9d67\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In the Toh 531 version of the text there is a slight discrepancy in the folio numbering between the 1737 par phud printings and the late (post par phud) printings of the Degé Kangyur. Although the discrepancy is irrelevant here, further details concerning this may be found in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":277}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.3\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":277,\"end\":280},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fc6d2d20-d3db-4e51-9b53-2728a75833f3\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/4d1896b2-dcf3-4b01-8cc6-8bd5e30c9d67\",\"entity\":\"4d1896b2-dcf3-4b01-8cc6-8bd5e30c9d67\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":\"toh21\",\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"3 of the Toh 531 version of this text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":280,\"end\":318}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6085c4ea-7fd1-419b-9ef0-596e57bb2249\",\"sort\":595,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.33\",\"toh\":\"toh531\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Homage to the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother! Thus did I hear at one time. The Blessed One was residing on Vulture Peak Mountain at Rājagṛha together with a great saṅgha of monks and a great saṅgha of bodhisattvas.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":251,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"900d66c8-caef-469f-911b-98cba686dcea\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-59\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":620,\"uuid\":\"6085c4ea-7fd1-419b-9ef0-596e57bb2249\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Two sets of folio references have been included in this translation due to a discrepancy in volume 88 (rg\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":105}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yud ’bum\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":113},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":113,\"uuid\":\"796bb75e-df28-4a85-bffa-3712ca6428de\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", na) of the Degé Kangyur betw\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":113,\"end\":143}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"een the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":143,\"end\":151},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":143,\"end\":151,\"uuid\":\"a1f27cda-3e34-4b92-b9dd-5b414cca1bd7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1737 par phud printings and the late (post par phud) printings. In the latter case, an extra work, Bodhi­maṇḍasyālaṃkāra­lakṣa­dhāraṇī (Toh 508, byang chub snying po’i rgyan ’bum gyi gzungs), was added as the second text in the volume, thereby displacing the pagination of all the following texts in the same volume by 17 folios. Since the eKangyur follows the later printing, both references have been provided, with the highlighted one linking to the eKangyur viewer.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":151,\"end\":620}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e08623fc-9546-4c0d-af84-c434fed7f74e\",\"sort\":601,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.34\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Homage to the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother! Thus did I hear at one time. The Blessed One was residing on Vulture Peak Mountain at Rājagṛha together with a great saṅgha of monks and a great saṅgha of bodhisattvas.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":251,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"900d66c8-caef-469f-911b-98cba686dcea\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-59\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"e08623fc-9546-4c0d-af84-c434fed7f74e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “Homage to all buddhas and bodhisattvas!”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":47}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7e1e441f-579d-4004-b44b-4dc16c3d01b3\",\"sort\":603,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.35\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"At that time the Blessed One rested in an absorption on the categories of phenomena called illumination of the profound.\",\"label\":\"1.2\",\"sort\":260,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"6377055b-2736-4d35-96d2-f5d908c2faae\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-63\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":621,\"uuid\":\"7e1e441f-579d-4004-b44b-4dc16c3d01b3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This sentence could also be translated: “At that time the Blessed One rested in a Dharma-discourse-absorption called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":117}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"illumination of the profound\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":145},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":145,\"uuid\":\"386ffc3c-2c3d-410e-b29c-2e69a70416af\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"distinct\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".” The Tengyur commentaries are all vague on this point but are united in glossing the term \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":145,\"end\":237}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dharmaparyāya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":237,\"end\":250},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":237,\"end\":250,\"uuid\":\"d80d341d-d7b4-4d59-8d55-5173dd222b57\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":250,\"end\":252}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"chos kyi rnam grangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":252,\"end\":272},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":252,\"end\":272,\"uuid\":\"0577d859-0ae6-4d5c-9f85-3100d94fb0bb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), which is often translated “Dharma discourse,” as a categorization of phenomena, rather than a Dharma teaching. We have therefore opted to follow this in our translation. In recension B, the sentence is quite different. Thus, Stok reads: “At that time the Blessed One rested in the absorption called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":272,\"end\":574}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"illumination of the profound Dharma discourse\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":574,\"end\":619},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":574,\"end\":619,\"uuid\":\"ab1f8236-4ab8-46f6-91fd-37b5876a3df5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"distinct\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":619,\"end\":621}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"168a2d26-d7dd-42d3-83c0-2ce174601c0c\",\"sort\":613,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.36\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"At the same time, the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, while practicing the profound perfection of wisdom, looked and saw that the five aggregates are also empty of an intrinsic nature.\",\"label\":\"1.3\",\"sort\":265,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"851efcc7-c043-4084-9a70-a2fc8d947a2e\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-65\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":323,\"uuid\":\"168a2d26-d7dd-42d3-83c0-2ce174601c0c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"At this point the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":50},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"38e79e1c-ab60-4869-b37c-de71eff9f2d4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" begins. In the long version, the first sentence of the short version is extended into a paragraph that incorporates the original in a new, expanded context. The texts converge at the second sentence of the standard text (beginning with “Form is empty. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":303}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":303,\"end\":312},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"5cc38ec5-44e9-447c-b523-46c5d420ce25\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is form”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":312,\"end\":323}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"024993e1-e913-490a-b99e-74785dd527cf\",\"sort\":619,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.37\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"At the same time, the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, while practicing the profound perfection of wisdom, looked and saw that the five aggregates are also empty of an intrinsic nature.\",\"label\":\"1.3\",\"sort\":265,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"851efcc7-c043-4084-9a70-a2fc8d947a2e\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-65\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":196,\"uuid\":\"024993e1-e913-490a-b99e-74785dd527cf\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vimalamitra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":24},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a\",\"uuid\":\"4c08e364-55fa-42a1-bfe2-7081352bc937\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s commentary, the word “also” indicates that \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":70}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":84},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"3ca34fc4-e065-4903-ae61-0bf76f4d0b52\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" also saw that the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":103}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sense sources\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":103,\"end\":116},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"325e169f-0289-4129-bf1b-f8c797380220\",\"uuid\":\"3f18d047-f6f8-4f4b-8ff2-4a34d99e0e6f\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":116,\"end\":125}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"elements\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":125,\"end\":133},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413\",\"uuid\":\"453a550c-e6a6-4c86-8018-eafa1c8359f4\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" likewise are empty of an intrinsic nature. (Toh 3818, F.271.a)\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":133,\"end\":196}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c33ea681-e70d-4c32-8ac1-d8b5d74a1bfd\",\"sort\":631,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.38\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"At the same time, the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, while practicing the profound perfection of wisdom, looked and saw that the five aggregates are also empty of an intrinsic nature.\",\"label\":\"1.3\",\"sort\":265,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"851efcc7-c043-4084-9a70-a2fc8d947a2e\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-65\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1080,\"uuid\":\"c33ea681-e70d-4c32-8ac1-d8b5d74a1bfd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “and he saw that the five \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"0b03b442-ab17-446c-a27f-1d44f72f90c7\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are empty of an essence.” On the variations of this sentence across the Sanskrit, Chinese, and Tibetan sources, see Attwood 2015. Our translation of the Tibetan agrees with Attwood’s proposed reading of the Sanskrit. However, unlike Attwood, we also believe that the same reading can be applied to the Tibetan text in both Recension A and Recension B. Besides simply making better sense overall, this reading is also supported by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":473}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vimalamitra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":473,\"end\":484},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a\",\"uuid\":\"5ffd4a4c-402e-4a93-937f-25cd160c1084\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s commentary on this passage (Toh 3818, F.270.a–F.271.b), and, moreover, it agrees semantically with the shorter version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":609}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":609,\"end\":624},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5155d34a-74d8-4a2b-826b-936607e9c411\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in Chinese, Sanskrit, and Tibetan. Attwood’s analysis of the Tibetan (2015, p. 40) therefore misreads the Tibetan, we would argue, as does Jonathan Silk’s translation of the same passage (1994, pp. 174–75) on which Attwood’s arguments are based. Several other translators, e.g., Donald Lopez (1996, p. vii) and Thupten Jinpa (Dalai Lama 2015, pp. 59–62), translate using the same reading as Silk, though not all (e.g., Nālandā Translation Committee 1980).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":624,\"end\":1080}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"05912d8d-f6a8-40cf-bb4d-fc2d8008c191\",\"sort\":641,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.39\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then, due to the Buddha’s power, venerable Śāriputra asked the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, “How should sons of noble family or daughters of noble family train if they wish to engage in the practice of the profound perfection of wisdom?”\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":276,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"95957669-a242-4f8d-a465-d771d99d1865\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-69\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23,\"uuid\":\"05912d8d-f6a8-40cf-bb4d-fc2d8008c191\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāradvatīputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9998ea3b-be7b-4ae9-abd9-6be2a6958171\",\"uuid\":\"b5b01bbb-e18d-45a5-a888-bdf8dae00eae\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":23}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e6651694-a300-4892-b24a-100258083023\",\"sort\":645,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.40\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then, due to the Buddha’s power, venerable Śāriputra asked the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, “How should sons of noble family or daughters of noble family train if they wish to engage in the practice of the profound perfection of wisdom?”\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":276,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"95957669-a242-4f8d-a465-d771d99d1865\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-69\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42,\"uuid\":\"e6651694-a300-4892-b24a-100258083023\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok omits “or daughters of noble family.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fb289d4f-3ec0-4b47-bc7f-b1fc7aed6652\",\"sort\":647,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.41\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, replied to venerable Śāradvatīputra, “Śāriputra, sons of noble family or daughters of noble family who wish to engage in the practice of the profound perfection of wisdom should see things in this way: they should correctly observe the five aggregates to be empty of an intrinsic nature.\",\"label\":\"1.5\",\"sort\":285,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ce892908-7d78-47bc-98f6-15ca9c5062dd\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-72\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":106,\"uuid\":\"fb289d4f-3ec0-4b47-bc7f-b1fc7aed6652\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The names \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāradvatīputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":24},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9998ea3b-be7b-4ae9-abd9-6be2a6958171\",\"uuid\":\"58b722f7-7a26-45c5-9d1c-06c02e66a239\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":38},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e\",\"uuid\":\"cd85584d-c584-45b3-8af2-15185c1218e1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are used interchangeably in the sūtras to refer to the same person.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":106}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"565899fd-b08a-4b36-a7d6-f4b338b709be\",\"sort\":653,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.42\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, replied to venerable Śāradvatīputra, “Śāriputra, sons of noble family or daughters of noble family who wish to engage in the practice of the profound perfection of wisdom should see things in this way: they should correctly observe the five aggregates to be empty of an intrinsic nature.\",\"label\":\"1.5\",\"sort\":285,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ce892908-7d78-47bc-98f6-15ca9c5062dd\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-72\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54,\"uuid\":\"565899fd-b08a-4b36-a7d6-f4b338b709be\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “the five \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":26},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"13fb413f-dbba-467c-bf36-11bb9c61c8d4\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to be empty of an essence.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":54}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"34bc3db5-e384-4b4b-8b05-dd795a4d2a77\",\"sort\":657,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.43\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Form is empty. Emptiness is form. Emptiness is not other than form, and form is also not other than emptiness. In the same way, feeling, perception, formation, and consciousness are empty.\",\"label\":\"1.6\",\"sort\":298,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"eb757806-fcfd-4a92-9cc4-321d0322921d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-75\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":297,\"uuid\":\"34bc3db5-e384-4b4b-8b05-dd795a4d2a77\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Both recensions A and B in Tibetan read “empty” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":49}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"stong pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"c3106b30-c944-4fde-b581-b9e5b5bff5ab\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") rather than “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":72}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":72,\"end\":81},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"7de04651-f130-41af-8078-3a498e96a6bf\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":84}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"stong pa nyid\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":97},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":97,\"uuid\":\"01a97322-6227-4ec4-938e-1c7918305232\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). Conze’s edition of the Sanskrit reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":97,\"end\":138}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"śūnyatā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":138,\"end\":145},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":138,\"end\":145,\"uuid\":\"be290fe7-26e3-4d6d-af9c-137aef35d2f2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":145,\"end\":148}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":148,\"end\":157},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"52669c80-719d-4101-9859-987aed8286e7\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”), although several sources read \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":191}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"śūnyam\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":191,\"end\":197},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":191,\"end\":197,\"uuid\":\"d4110feb-39e7-4326-9b8e-f8836270b0da\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“empty”) (1967, p. 150, note 10). Taishō 250 and 251 both read “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":197,\"end\":263}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":263,\"end\":272},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"0162ed57-b981-4ede-8774-0d8d9c4b2cae\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"” (Attwood 2017b, p. 56).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":272,\"end\":297}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1984c433-95a8-4026-81fe-1cd0ab3ba34e\",\"sort\":673,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.44\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Form is empty. Emptiness is form. Emptiness is not other than form, and form is also not other than emptiness. In the same way, feeling, perception, formation, and consciousness are empty.\",\"label\":\"1.6\",\"sort\":298,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"eb757806-fcfd-4a92-9cc4-321d0322921d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-75\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":892,\"uuid\":\"1984c433-95a8-4026-81fe-1cd0ab3ba34e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"On these four sentences, see Attwood 2017b where their origins in earlier Prajñāpāramitā literature are traced. This way of articulating the relationship between \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":162}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":162,\"end\":171},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"0de4132f-6110-420e-8acf-8b1e5fda40aa\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the phenomena of the five \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":171,\"end\":202}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":202,\"end\":212},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"2f607cc8-5521-4502-a186-ad8425033758\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" echoes sets of passages in all three of the long Prajñāpāramitā sūtras. In two passages in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":212,\"end\":304}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":304,\"end\":355},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ecd657c2-bda5-499e-bd14-d9ad42c76f51\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 10, 3.23 and 8.14), two in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":355,\"end\":388}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":388,\"end\":442},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ebe1d6cf-62f9-4f59-acae-05ed34130498\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 9, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":442,\"end\":451}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2.112\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":451,\"end\":456},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b7f544e8-ee06-42ef-8db0-3d37835e182d\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/6e96c7fc-df67-4185-bc68-53b6cbe6057f\",\"entity\":\"6e96c7fc-df67-4185-bc68-53b6cbe6057f\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"–\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":456,\"end\":457}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2.117\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":457,\"end\":462},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4ef01e07-8ca3-43c1-900f-8d1b2a143cae\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/7920c835-4878-4812-a7be-ddb1f0c3f557\",\"entity\":\"7920c835-4878-4812-a7be-ddb1f0c3f557\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":462,\"end\":467}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"6.11\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":467,\"end\":471},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0a411d29-9ca3-4763-99c0-1fb192418220\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/568aadb5-1303-43dc-aa58-7300842ffaf0\",\"entity\":\"568aadb5-1303-43dc-aa58-7300842ffaf0\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), and three in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":471,\"end\":487}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":487,\"end\":541},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e75ba702-f5d8-4e09-86c7-1b41a3334fd8\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 8, 2.191–2.196, 2.238–2.245, and 5.191-5.212) there are similarly statements to the effect that \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":541,\"end\":643}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":643,\"end\":652},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"4d763165-d015-421b-b8dd-afc0e9cb3324\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is not other than form, that form itself is \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":652,\"end\":697}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":697,\"end\":706},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"f13749fe-ded3-4aa4-ae13-63073c9ffb32\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":706,\"end\":712}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":712,\"end\":721},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"5a0ab360-deaf-424f-a3c1-10a4f0a87943\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" itself is form. Those passages go on to characterize the relationship between \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":721,\"end\":800}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":800,\"end\":809},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"32c6aafb-37fb-4bce-81c2-cd0903453469\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the other \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":809,\"end\":824}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":824,\"end\":834},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"4843ee2d-0009-4ccf-a3bb-a9fde0f21f95\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and all other phenomena, in the same way. See also \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":834,\"end\":887}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.49\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":887,\"end\":891},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f7490f1f-a661-49cc-9b4f-cac8a5cf9f09\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/c06efba5-a82c-424f-9440-addf2bc9de86\",\"entity\":\"c06efba5-a82c-424f-9440-addf2bc9de86\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":891,\"end\":892}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9b188205-b62e-442f-bd16-5031433dfebd\",\"sort\":719,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.45\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Form is empty. Emptiness is form. Emptiness is not other than form, and form is also not other than emptiness. In the same way, feeling, perception, formation, and consciousness are empty.\",\"label\":\"1.6\",\"sort\":298,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"eb757806-fcfd-4a92-9cc4-321d0322921d\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-75\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19,\"uuid\":\"9b188205-b62e-442f-bd16-5031433dfebd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “formations.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9354294e-9ee9-4926-bd53-8a97f19e97e4\",\"sort\":721,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.46\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Śāriputra, therefore, all phenomena are emptiness; they are without characteristics, unborn, unceasing, without stains, without absence of stains, not deficient, and not complete.\",\"label\":\"1.7\",\"sort\":312,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3943ad51-3f3d-4e01-b913-3a5a9ceefdf5\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-79\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"9354294e-9ee9-4926-bd53-8a97f19e97e4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “free from stains, without stains.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"75b57a5e-61cf-4ffb-bebe-53bdb52e3194\",\"sort\":723,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.47\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“There is no element of the eye, up to no element of the mind, and further up to no element of the mind consciousness.\",\"label\":\"1.9\",\"sort\":326,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"2bc29a07-d54f-4df1-9847-682d5a2aa5ac\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-82\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":150,\"uuid\":\"75b57a5e-61cf-4ffb-bebe-53bdb52e3194\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “There is no \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"element\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":26},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413\",\"uuid\":\"a4f2dd2c-3b7e-4941-9184-c8f140bf6307\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" of the eye and no \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":45}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"element\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413\",\"uuid\":\"f3276fcb-ebaa-4ff0-aa40-95b5285885ba\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" of the eye consciousness, up to no \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":88}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"element\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":95},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413\",\"uuid\":\"74c7465d-b99c-4c9c-a12a-dca12b327ecb\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" of the mind and no \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":95,\"end\":115}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"element\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":115,\"end\":122},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413\",\"uuid\":\"2dc0c752-9d7b-4ee2-b7c6-b19611a8dd02\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" of the mind consciousness.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":122,\"end\":150}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5b7db543-5f2e-4b1b-a9c7-be364b887a66\",\"sort\":733,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.48\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“There is no suffering, no origin of suffering, no cessation of suffering, no path, no wisdom, no attainment, and no nonattainment.\",\"label\":\"1.11\",\"sort\":339,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c8dc6454-a277-4416-befe-f986df4ee096\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-85\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"5b7db543-5f2e-4b1b-a9c7-be364b887a66\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “no cognition.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c06efba5-a82c-424f-9440-addf2bc9de86\",\"sort\":735,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.49\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“There is no suffering, no origin of suffering, no cessation of suffering, no path, no wisdom, no attainment, and no nonattainment.\",\"label\":\"1.11\",\"sort\":339,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c8dc6454-a277-4416-befe-f986df4ee096\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-85\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":844,\"uuid\":\"c06efba5-a82c-424f-9440-addf2bc9de86\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This series of negations echoes the more extensive series found in passages in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":130},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7d22b3f2-d218-46ac-9cdb-7a644b9ecedb\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 10, 3.24–3.28), in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":130,\"end\":155}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":155,\"end\":209},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2566ae4a-b09f-4a2f-a587-c7b27b9e4396\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 9, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":209,\"end\":218}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2.113\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":218,\"end\":223},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d81d55bb-87d5-46a6-b326-3c3f5e45d2b0\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/8386d6f7-41e2-49cd-a1fe-0695c9b26f8c\",\"entity\":\"8386d6f7-41e2-49cd-a1fe-0695c9b26f8c\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"–\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":223,\"end\":224}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2.117\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":224,\"end\":229},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0b826bd9-41a3-47a1-8377-45490eb253f3\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/7920c835-4878-4812-a7be-ddb1f0c3f557\",\"entity\":\"7920c835-4878-4812-a7be-ddb1f0c3f557\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), and in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":229,\"end\":239}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":239,\"end\":293},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0cade746-0fa5-4bda-8d8a-f6634178639d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 8, 2.191–2.193), which also begin by negating each of the five \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":293,\"end\":362}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":362,\"end\":372},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"ece70527-1fc1-4110-b28f-af0aa3557962\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The series of negations there is immediately preceded by a passage declaring that each of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":372,\"end\":468}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":468,\"end\":478},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"a22a21ee-4007-4412-9468-266773e26e24\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" “is not one thing and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":478,\"end\":501}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":501,\"end\":510},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"462f63d4-678a-46bc-ae64-447ceddb4f63\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" another,” since each of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":510,\"end\":539}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":539,\"end\":549},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"802d5719-7e51-4b90-be61-8b8c8775c735\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" “is itself \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":549,\"end\":561}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":561,\"end\":570},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"85b47363-6824-4c0a-9c17-32627096bfb7\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",” and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":570,\"end\":577}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":577,\"end\":586},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"2d60ca21-4108-417b-879c-a0d761694ae3\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is each of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":586,\"end\":602}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aggregates\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":602,\"end\":612},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"uuid\":\"03a4a7c6-d8cd-4b6c-aec6-009a1746c7eb\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". See also \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":612,\"end\":623}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.44\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":623,\"end\":627},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1a616ee5-80b3-4faf-bb30-6cd492fccdf9\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/1984c433-95a8-4026-81fe-1cd0ab3ba34e\",\"entity\":\"1984c433-95a8-4026-81fe-1cd0ab3ba34e\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". See also Shi 2014 who analyzes earlier Chinese translations of Prajñāpāramitā literature to argue for a new translation of the terms “no nonattainment” in this sentence and “no attainment” in the following sentence.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":627,\"end\":844}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"76271c11-98e2-4862-927c-7b4427cd7e5f\",\"sort\":771,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.50\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Śāriputra, therefore, since bodhisattvas have no attainment, they rely upon and dwell in the perfection of wisdom. Because their minds have no veils, they have no fear. Having utterly gone beyond error, they reach the culmination of nirvāṇa.\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":344,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"68dbe41a-5817-4160-ba54-68f8fd696570\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-88\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"76271c11-98e2-4862-927c-7b4427cd7e5f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “they rely upon the perfection of wisdom.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"675263fc-d1c8-48e3-bc14-5c92df414eb5\",\"sort\":773,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.51\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Śāriputra, therefore, since bodhisattvas have no attainment, they rely upon and dwell in the perfection of wisdom. Because their minds have no veils, they have no fear. Having utterly gone beyond error, they reach the culmination of nirvāṇa.\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":344,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"68dbe41a-5817-4160-ba54-68f8fd696570\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-88\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"675263fc-d1c8-48e3-bc14-5c92df414eb5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok omits “utterly.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c3e7a50-33b1-4ff6-95b4-4b88172b7982\",\"sort\":775,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.52\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Therefore, the mantra of the perfection of wisdom is the mantra of great knowledge, the unsurpassed mantra, the mantra that is equal to the unequaled, and the mantra that utterly pacifies all suffering. Since it is not false, it should be known to be true.\",\"label\":\"1.14\",\"sort\":354,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"e351e324-217d-4bd9-9aa3-129b29839640\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-92\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29,\"uuid\":\"0c3e7a50-33b1-4ff6-95b4-4b88172b7982\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":16},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e\",\"uuid\":\"07a4fa12-4b66-4ad8-88ee-5d6a482c642c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", therefore.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":29}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9a522107-27ec-4868-8bdc-b624abf3c462\",\"sort\":779,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.53\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Therefore, the mantra of the perfection of wisdom is the mantra of great knowledge, the unsurpassed mantra, the mantra that is equal to the unequaled, and the mantra that utterly pacifies all suffering. Since it is not false, it should be known to be true.\",\"label\":\"1.14\",\"sort\":354,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"e351e324-217d-4bd9-9aa3-129b29839640\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-92\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":331,\"uuid\":\"9a522107-27ec-4868-8bdc-b624abf3c462\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Attwood (2017a) has argued that the term \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mantra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"8fba5cdc-ef43-4868-bec8-1344b5f5ddf8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":51}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":66},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c46a5c71-c046-41c6-9632-17e279f3afff\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" most likely is a mistranslation of the Chinese rendering of the term \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":136}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vidyā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":136,\"end\":141},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":136,\"end\":141,\"uuid\":\"3c198745-8e56-4533-b5e6-ade02c45a215\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", because this is what appears in Sanskrit manuscripts of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":141,\"end\":203}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":203,\"end\":257},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b501a6b3-d541-4b38-aea1-ebdf89da3f16\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and because of how Kumārajīva phrases it in his translation of that text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":257,\"end\":331}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"61caee6c-81ff-45eb-b5be-ed61d424afaa\",\"sort\":789,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.54\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The mantra of the perfection of wisdom is stated thus: tadyathā gate gate pāragate pārasaṃgate bodhi svāhā\",\"label\":\"1.15\",\"sort\":360,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ff35fd29-08f8-47c5-b129-f6c90c6a734f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-95\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":151,\"uuid\":\"61caee6c-81ff-45eb-b5be-ed61d424afaa\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Instead of these last two sentences, Stok reads: “The perfection of wisdom, which is without error, should be known as a true mantra and as knowledge.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":151}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6527bb40-f128-450a-a3be-933a63434947\",\"sort\":791,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.55\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The mantra of the perfection of wisdom is stated thus: tadyathā gate gate pāragate pārasaṃgate bodhi svāhā\",\"label\":\"1.15\",\"sort\":360,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ff35fd29-08f8-47c5-b129-f6c90c6a734f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-95\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":267,\"uuid\":\"6527bb40-f128-450a-a3be-933a63434947\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Most witnesses of Recension A (though not the versions in the Degé Kangyur, nor the versions in Choné, Lhasa, Lithang, or Urga) include the syllable \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":149}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"oṁ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":151},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":151,\"uuid\":\"607fd9ac-882f-4d7e-a41b-317a9cb369af\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" after \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":151,\"end\":158}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tadyathā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":158,\"end\":166},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":158,\"end\":166,\"uuid\":\"450a583b-0b92-48a3-a977-1e81594a3e13\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". See Silk 1994, p. 138. None of the Chinese sources include \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":166,\"end\":227}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"oṁ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":227,\"end\":229},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":227,\"end\":229,\"uuid\":\"e6d99ee7-68b2-4552-92fc-e3456e548d48\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" whereas some Sanskrit manuscripts do.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":229,\"end\":267}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"942aca84-15a7-4f68-a94e-e207c74c516c\",\"sort\":799,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.56\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“The mantra of the perfection of wisdom is stated thus: tadyathā gate gate pāragate pārasaṃgate bodhi svāhā\",\"label\":\"1.15\",\"sort\":360,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ff35fd29-08f8-47c5-b129-f6c90c6a734f\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-95\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":175,\"uuid\":\"942aca84-15a7-4f68-a94e-e207c74c516c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This mantra can be rendered in English as “Like this: gone, gone, gone beyond, utterly gone beyond. Awakening. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":111}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Svāhā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":116},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":116,\"uuid\":\"51e392a0-5f86-4fb6-8a8d-aaf1d63e9cbd\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".” At this point the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":116,\"end\":154}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":154,\"end\":169},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a1662d04-afa5-419b-80ca-5601b4b73d9e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" ends.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":169,\"end\":175}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4f03546e-bfcc-42c6-82bd-0c71ba145968\",\"sort\":805,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.57\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Then the Blessed One arose from that absorption and gave his approval to the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, saying, “Excellent! Excellent! Son of noble family, it is like that. Son of noble family, it is like that. The profound perfection of wisdom should be practiced just as you have taught, and even the thus-gone ones will rejoice.”\",\"label\":\"1.17\",\"sort\":372,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"78e150b0-117a-4392-b695-e68dfe649560\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-101\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":55,\"uuid\":\"4f03546e-bfcc-42c6-82bd-0c71ba145968\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Before “Excellent,” Stok inserts “Son of noble family.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":55}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"05fd95a6-6a77-4e6d-8fba-4c45817e16e6\",\"sort\":807,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.58\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"When the Blessed One had said this, venerable Śāradvatīputra, the bodhisattva great being, noble Avalokiteśvara, and the entire assembly, as well as the world with its devas, humans, asuras, and gandharvas, rejoiced and praised what the Blessed One had said.\",\"label\":\"1.18\",\"sort\":378,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c5f37d38-04fd-4dee-bd78-dcc1339ac3f2\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-103\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"05fd95a6-6a77-4e6d-8fba-4c45817e16e6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok: “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":16},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e\",\"uuid\":\"0bc1e025-1455-4062-a621-b02d23183be8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":18}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c5ad6e00-1386-40fa-9964-be828c055e4d\",\"sort\":811,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.59\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"This was translated by the Indian preceptor Vimalamitra and the translator monk Rinchen Dé, and then edited and finalized by the editor-translators Gelo, Namkha, and others. It was then carefully proofed against the writing on the wall of the Gegye Jema Ling Temple at glorious Samye‍—the spontaneously accomplished temple.\",\"label\":\"c.1\",\"sort\":393,\"type\":\"colophon\",\"uuid\":\"3556ba50-15cd-4c99-9e63-e0e1176e2f69\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-106\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":801,\"uuid\":\"c5ad6e00-1386-40fa-9964-be828c055e4d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The “writing on the wall of the Gegye Jema Ling Temple” is a reference to a Sanskrit version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":96}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":111},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a2c2559b-b475-4c41-a1ec-19da9aecc8a3\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" written on one of the walls in the Gegye Jema Ling (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":164}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dge rgyas bye ma gling\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":164,\"end\":186},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":164,\"end\":186,\"uuid\":\"75d07fd6-3c1b-46c6-b41d-32958c9a31f2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") Temple at Samye Monastery. That the writing was in Sanskrit, and that the comparison of the translation to that Sanskrit text took place “at a later time,” is mentioned in the catalogs (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":186,\"end\":374}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dkar chag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":374,\"end\":383},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":374,\"end\":383,\"uuid\":\"42d0575d-b81e-4418-92ed-3ae00023103e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") of the Narthang, Degé, Urga, and Lhasa Kangyurs. The earliest of these is the Narthang catalog, written by the Lelung Jedrung Lobzang Trinlé (1690–1740), which specifies that the version on the wall was the one “with introduction” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":383,\"end\":617}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gleng gzhi’i bkod pa dang bcas bris pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":617,\"end\":655},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":617,\"end\":655,\"uuid\":\"e8136e70-feb9-47cc-b649-0165d25f6ce8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; see Narthang \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":655,\"end\":670}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dkar chag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":670,\"end\":679},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":670,\"end\":679,\"uuid\":\"8b504e14-cfee-41fe-afcd-50c7c8e9ffd5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" F.85.b). For the mention in the Degé catalog, see Degé Kangyur vol. 103 (lakṣmī), F.118.b. See also Silk 1994, pp. 48–49.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":679,\"end\":801}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0de07b43-cd8e-4501-bc2e-f6e08f863ada\",\"sort\":823,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.60\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"This was translated by the Indian preceptor Vimalamitra and the translator monk Rinchen Dé, and then edited and finalized by the editor-translators Gelo, Namkha, and others. It was then carefully proofed against the writing on the wall of the Gegye Jema Ling Temple at glorious Samye‍—the spontaneously accomplished temple.\",\"label\":\"c.1\",\"sort\":393,\"type\":\"colophon\",\"uuid\":\"3556ba50-15cd-4c99-9e63-e0e1176e2f69\",\"workUuid\":\"6b374ae7-ddfa-4de4-b7f8-98f7635a3849\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-034-009-106\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"0de07b43-cd8e-4501-bc2e-f6e08f863ada\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This colophon is missing in Stok.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33}}]}]}],\"glossary\":[{\"uuid\":\"9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3\",\"authority\":\"befb80a6-3a70-411f-84f4-2016cc3a88fa\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eFive “collections” that encompass all apparent physical and mental phenomena: form, feeling, perception, formation(s), and consciousness.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aggregate\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕུང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"skandha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phung po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"authority\":\"0ecba1e9-f6bc-4e30-823b-34a3dc139974\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eOne of the “eight close sons of the Buddha,” he is also known as the bodhisattva who embodies compassion. In certain tantras, he is also the lord of the three families, where he embodies the compassion of the buddhas. In Tibet, he attained great significance as a special protector of Tibet, and in China, in female form, as Guanyin, the most important bodhisattva in all of East Asia.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྱན་རས་གཟིགས་དབང་ཕྱུག\",\"sanskrit\":\"avalokiteśvara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spyan ras gzigs dbang phyug\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413\",\"authority\":\"e3685c95-a735-4cb3-a0e7-d0d5dc0b3295\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne way of describing experience and the world in terms of eighteen elements: eye, form, and eye consciousness; ear, sound, and ear consciousness; nose, odor, and nose consciousness; tongue, taste, and tongue consciousness; body, touch, and body consciousness; and mind, mental objects, and mind consciousness. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"element\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁམས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhātu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khams\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"authority\":\"73d1ceda-eda2-4181-ad71-d9c09c063106\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eEmptiness denotes the ultimate nature of reality, the total absence of inherent existence and self-identity with respect to all phenomena. According to this view, all things and events are devoid of any independent, intrinsic reality that constitutes their essence. Nothing can be said to exist independent of the complex network of factors that gives rise to its origination, nor are phenomena independent of the cognitive processes and mental constructs that make up the conventional framework within which their identity and existence are posited. When all levels of conceptualization dissolve and when all forms of dichotomizing tendencies are quelled through deliberate meditative deconstruction of conceptual elaborations, the ultimate nature of reality will finally become manifest. It is the first of the three gateways to liberation.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"emptiness\",\"tibetan\":\"སྟོང་པ་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śūnyatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"stong pa nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c958e40c-5676-47df-9050-f81e78568049\",\"authority\":\"49b4dd9d-6943-4324-8077-38c956a4546c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eEighth-century Tibetan editor of Toh 21.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gelo\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བློ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge blo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"12e65098-d92a-4c4e-880b-af900b9b8f3a\",\"authority\":\"26ab078a-a4ce-4bbb-afcc-6d1c491a390d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eEighth-century Tibetan editor of Toh 21.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Namkha\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"00a8c52d-7629-4286-8237-9f6bd87d18d3\",\"authority\":\"b5a161b5-2aa7-4c37-a473-82556d4a3e8b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe ancient capital of Magadha prior to its relocation to Pāṭaliputra during the Mauryan dynasty, Rājagṛha is one of the most important locations in Buddhist history. The literature tells us that the Buddha and his saṅgha spent a considerable amount of time in residence in and around Rājagṛha‍—in nearby places, such as the Vulture Peak Mountain (Gṛdhrakūṭaparvata), a major site of the Mahāyāna sūtras, and the Bamboo Grove (Veṇuvana)‍—enjoying the patronage of King Bimbisāra and then of his son King Ajātaśatru. Rājagṛha is also remembered as the location where the first Buddhist monastic council was held after the Buddha Śākyamuni passed into parinirvāṇa. Now known as Rajgir and located in the modern Indian state of Bihar.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Rājagṛha\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་པོའི་ཁབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"rājagṛha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal po’i khab\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b3a43e78-559c-44a4-a203-e14d6ee55eac\",\"authority\":\"8e1d7838-8588-4f4b-97b3-d368c067bef8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eEighth-century Tibetan translator of Toh 21.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Rinchen Dé\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་ཆེན་སྡེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin chen sde\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9998ea3b-be7b-4ae9-abd9-6be2a6958171\",\"authority\":\"c32889b0-83bb-4c7e-8fa5-4bb526bcf3c9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eOne of the principal śrāvaka disciples of the Buddha, he was renowned for his discipline and for having been praised by the Buddha as foremost of the wise (often paired with Maudgalyā­yana, who was praised as foremost in the capacity for miraculous powers). His father, Tiṣya, to honor Śāriputra’s mother, Śārikā, named him Śāradvatīputra, or, in its contracted form, Śāriputra, meaning “Śārikā’s Son.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śāradvatīputra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤ་ར་དྭ་ཏིའི་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śāradvatīputra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sha ra dwa ti’i bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e\",\"authority\":\"028f92a7-eb1f-4d2a-9d19-a4c4c188481c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso known as \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-034-009-146\\\"\u003eŚāradvatīputra\u003c/span\u003e. He was one of the closest disciples of the Buddha, known for his pure discipline and, of the hearer disciples, considered foremost in wisdom.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śāriputra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śāriputra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shA ri’i bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"325e169f-0289-4129-bf1b-f8c797380220\",\"authority\":\"98a2a6bf-fbf2-44ff-bddd-c53418bf76d5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThese can be listed as twelve or as six sense sources (sometimes also called sense fields, bases of cognition, or simply āyatanas).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn the context of epistemology, it is one way of describing experience and the world in terms of twelve sense sources, which can be divided into inner and outer sense sources, namely: (1–2) eye and form, (3–4) ear and sound, (5–6) nose and odor, (7–8) tongue and taste, (9–10) body and touch, (11–12) mind and mental phenomena.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn the context of the twelve links of dependent origination, only six sense sources are mentioned, and they are the inner sense sources (identical to the six faculties) of eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sense sources\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེ་མཆེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āyatana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skye mched\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a\",\"authority\":\"6490cabc-c79c-4142-b919-29eff9328e68\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eEighth/ninth-century Indian master important in the transmission of Buddhism to Tibet.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vimalamitra\",\"tibetan\":\"བི་མ་ལ་མི་ཏྲ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimalamitra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bi ma la mi tra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"faf044bb-e030-4ea8-9a1f-f12b9b0672d6\",\"authority\":\"260cb623-12cc-40a0-acf0-ce0b1a47aceb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe Gṛdhra­kūṭa, literally Vulture Peak, was a hill located in the kingdom of Magadha, in the vicinity of the ancient city of Rājagṛha (modern-day Rajgir, in the state of Bihar, India), where the Buddha bestowed many sūtras, especially the Great Vehicle teachings, such as the Prajñāpāramitā sūtras. It continues to be a sacred pilgrimage site for Buddhists to this day.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vulture Peak Mountain\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱ་རྒོད་ཕུང་པོའི་རི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gṛdhrakūṭaparvata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bya rgod phung po’i ri\"}}]}]\n"])</script><div hidden id="S:5"><div dir="ltr" data-orientation="horizontal" data-slot="tabs" class="flex flex-col w-full gap-0 @container/sidebar"><div class="sticky top-0 pt-1 pb-2 z-10 w-full rounded-t bg-background overflow-x-auto text-center"><div role="tablist" aria-orientation="horizontal" data-slot="tabs-list" class="bg-background gap-1 sm:gap-3 h-10 items-center justify-center sm:p-1 w-fit px-6 inline-flex mx-auto rounded-none" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" style="outline:none"><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="true" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-endnotes" data-state="active" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-endnotes" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 bg-background text-foreground border-b-2 border-transparent data-[state=active]:border-primary-300 decoration-primary-25 hover:text-primary hover:border-primary/20 hover:cursor-pointer" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" data-radix-collection-item="">Notes</button><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-glossary" data-state="inactive" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-glossary" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 bg-background text-foreground border-b-2 border-transparent data-[state=active]:border-primary-300 decoration-primary-25 hover:text-primary hover:border-primary/20 hover:cursor-pointer" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" data-radix-collection-item="">Glossary</button><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-bibliography" data-state="inactive" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-bibliography" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 bg-background text-foreground border-b-2 border-transparent data-[state=active]:border-primary-300 decoration-primary-25 hover:text-primary hover:border-primary/20 hover:cursor-pointer" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" data-radix-collection-item="">Biblio</button></div></div><div class="px-2"><div class="overflow-auto md:h-[calc(100vh-8.5rem)] h-[calc(100vh-4rem)] rounded bg-surface"><div class="rounded ps-10 pe-4 max-w-readable mx-auto"><div data-state="active" data-orientation="horizontal" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-endnotes" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-endnotes" tabindex="0" data-slot="tabs-content" class="mt-2 ring-offset-background focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 data-[state=inactive]:hidden" style="animation-duration:0s"><div class="h-0"></div><div></div><div class="h-0"></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-4 pb-8"><div class="flex gap-5"><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-6 w-6"></div><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-32 grow"></div></div><div class="flex gap-5"><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-6 w-6"></div><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-32 grow"></div></div><div class="flex gap-5"><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-6 w-6"></div><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-32 grow"></div></div></div></div><div data-state="inactive" data-orientation="horizontal" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-glossary" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-glossary" tabindex="0" data-slot="tabs-content" class="mt-2 ring-offset-background focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 pb-8 data-[state=inactive]:hidden"><div class="flex flex-col w-full"><div id="glossary" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2lanpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-5 mt-6">g.</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><h2 class="font-serif font-light text-primary scroll-m-20 text-xl @c/sidebar:mt-4 mt-6 @c/sidebar:pb-2 pb-3 @c/sidebar:text-left text-center section-title">Glossary</h2></div></div><div class="mt-3 flex flex-col gap-6"><div id="9a2298bf-1466-4e8f-9bbb-82d588aff4a3" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">aggregate</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">phung po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཕུང་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">skandha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Five “collections” that encompass all apparent physical and mental phenomena: form, feeling, perception, formation(s), and consciousness.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Avalokiteśvara</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">spyan ras gzigs dbang phyug</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྤྱན་རས་གཟིགས་དབང་ཕྱུག</span></li><li class="italic">avalokiteśvara</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>One of the “eight close sons of the Buddha,” he is also known as the bodhisattva who embodies compassion. In certain tantras, he is also the lord of the three families, where he embodies the compassion of the buddhas. In Tibet, he attained great significance as a special protector of Tibet, and in China, in female form, as Guanyin, the most important bodhisattva in all of East Asia.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="4c329be4-54f3-4631-adba-c73348323413" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">element</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">khams</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཁམས།</span></li><li class="italic">dhātu</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">One way of describing experience and the world in terms of eighteen elements: eye, form, and eye consciousness; ear, sound, and ear consciousness; nose, odor, and nose consciousness; tongue, taste, and tongue consciousness; body, touch, and body consciousness; and mind, mental objects, and mind consciousness. </p></div></div></div></div><div id="c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_555anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.4</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">emptiness</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">stong pa nyid</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྟོང་པ་ཉིད།</span></li><li class="italic">śūnyatā</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>Emptiness denotes the ultimate nature of reality, the total absence of inherent existence and self-identity with respect to all phenomena. According to this view, all things and events are devoid of any independent, intrinsic reality that constitutes their essence. Nothing can be said to exist independent of the complex network of factors that gives rise to its origination, nor are phenomena independent of the cognitive processes and mental constructs that make up the conventional framework within which their identity and existence are posited. When all levels of conceptualization dissolve and when all forms of dichotomizing tendencies are quelled through deliberate meditative deconstruction of conceptual elaborations, the ultimate nature of reality will finally become manifest. It is the first of the three gateways to liberation.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="c958e40c-5676-47df-9050-f81e78568049" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.5</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Gelo</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dge blo</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དགེ་བློ།</span></li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Eighth-century Tibetan editor of Toh 21.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="12e65098-d92a-4c4e-880b-af900b9b8f3a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.6</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Namkha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">nam mkha’</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ནམ་མཁའ།</span></li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Eighth-century Tibetan editor of Toh 21.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="00a8c52d-7629-4286-8237-9f6bd87d18d3" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.7</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Rājagṛha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rgyal po’i khab</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རྒྱལ་པོའི་ཁབ།</span></li><li class="italic">rājagṛha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>The ancient capital of Magadha prior to its relocation to Pāṭaliputra during the Mauryan dynasty, Rājagṛha is one of the most important locations in Buddhist history. The literature tells us that the Buddha and his saṅgha spent a considerable amount of time in residence in and around Rājagṛha‍—in nearby places, such as the Vulture Peak Mountain (Gṛdhrakūṭaparvata), a major site of the Mahāyāna sūtras, and the Bamboo Grove (Veṇuvana)‍—enjoying the patronage of King Bimbisāra and then of his son King Ajātaśatru. Rājagṛha is also remembered as the location where the first Buddhist monastic council was held after the Buddha Śākyamuni passed into parinirvāṇa. Now known as Rajgir and located in the modern Indian state of Bihar.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="b3a43e78-559c-44a4-a203-e14d6ee55eac" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_655anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.8</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Rinchen Dé</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rin chen sde</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རིན་ཆེན་སྡེ།</span></li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Eighth-century Tibetan translator of Toh 21.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="9998ea3b-be7b-4ae9-abd9-6be2a6958171" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.9</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Śāradvatīputra</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">sha ra dwa ti’i bu</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཤ་ར་དྭ་ཏིའི་བུ།</span></li><li class="italic">śāradvatīputra</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>One of the principal śrāvaka disciples of the Buddha, he was renowned for his discipline and for having been praised by the Buddha as foremost of the wise (often paired with Maudgalyā­yana, who was praised as foremost in the capacity for miraculous powers). His father, Tiṣya, to honor Śāriputra’s mother, Śārikā, named him Śāradvatīputra, or, in its contracted form, Śāriputra, meaning “Śārikā’s Son.”</p></div></div></div></div><div id="34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.10</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Śāriputra</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">shA ri’i bu</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ།</span></li><li class="italic">śāriputra</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Also known as <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-034-009-146">Śāradvatīputra</span>. He was one of the closest disciples of the Buddha, known for his pure discipline and, of the hearer disciples, considered foremost in wisdom.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="325e169f-0289-4129-bf1b-f8c797380220" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.11</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">sense sources</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">skye mched</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྐྱེ་མཆེད།</span></li><li class="italic">āyatana</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>These can be listed as twelve or as six sense sources (sometimes also called sense fields, bases of cognition, or simply āyatanas).</p><p>In the context of epistemology, it is one way of describing experience and the world in terms of twelve sense sources, which can be divided into inner and outer sense sources, namely: (1–2) eye and form, (3–4) ear and sound, (5–6) nose and odor, (7–8) tongue and taste, (9–10) body and touch, (11–12) mind and mental phenomena.</p><p>In the context of the twelve links of dependent origination, only six sense sources are mentioned, and they are the inner sense sources (identical to the six faculties) of eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_755anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.12</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Vimalamitra</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bi ma la mi tra</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བི་མ་ལ་མི་ཏྲ།</span></li><li class="italic">vimalamitra</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Eighth/ninth-century Indian master important in the transmission of Buddhism to Tibet.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="faf044bb-e030-4ea8-9a1f-f12b9b0672d6" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_7d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.13</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Vulture Peak Mountain</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bya rgod phung po’i ri</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བྱ་རྒོད་ཕུང་པོའི་རི།</span></li><li class="italic">gṛdhrakūṭaparvata</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>The Gṛdhra­kūṭa, literally Vulture Peak, was a hill located in the kingdom of Magadha, in the vicinity of the ancient city of Rājagṛha (modern-day Rajgir, in the state of Bihar, India), where the Buddha bestowed many sūtras, especially the Great Vehicle teachings, such as the Prajñāpāramitā sūtras. It continues to be a sacred pilgrimage site for Buddhists to this day.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-state="inactive" data-orientation="horizontal" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-bibliography" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-bibliography" tabindex="0" data-slot="tabs-content" class="mt-2 ring-offset-background focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 pb-8 data-[state=inactive]:hidden"><div class="flex flex-col w-full"><div id="bibliography" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2nanpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-5 mt-6">b.</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><h2 class="font-serif font-light text-primary scroll-m-20 text-xl @c/sidebar:mt-4 mt-6 @c/sidebar:pb-2 pb-3 @c/sidebar:text-left text-center section-title">Bibliography</h2></div></div><div class="mt-3 flex flex-col gap-6"><div class="flex flex-col gap-4"><div id="Tibetan Canonical Texts-0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5d7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-0.5 mt-4">b.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Tibetan Canonical Texts</div></div></div><div id="7e1dfdcd-beaa-434c-8496-baa971f90caf" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_16d7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p><em>bcom ldan ’das ma shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po bam po gcig go</em>. Toh 21, Degé Kangyur vol. 34 (sher phyin, ka), folios 144b–146a.</p></div></div></div><div id="1595a411-a9e2-4e96-ba6e-27f511e77904" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ad7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p><em>bcom ldan ’das ma shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po bam po gcig go</em>. Toh 531, Degé Kangyur vol. 88 (rgyud, na), folios 77b–78b.</p></div></div></div><div id="3287ad36-71dd-4e3f-bc51-920ec7a66c9f" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ed7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p><em>’phags pa shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po</em>. Stok no. 28, Stok Palace Kangyur vol. 51 (sras sna tshogs, ka), folios 277a–278b.</p></div></div></div><div id="d21c265e-05be-44b7-8ae1-c0516348d26e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1id7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.4</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Denkarma (<em>pho brang stod thang ldan [/ lhan] dkar gyi chos ’gyur ro cog gi dkar chag</em>). Degé Tengyur vol. 206 (sna tshogs, jo), folios 294b–310a.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-4"><div id="Secondary Sources-1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-0.5 mt-4">b.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Secondary Sources</div></div></div><div id="ae29dfd6-905c-4f79-863f-3a6208aa3a82" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_46l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “Heart Murmurs: Some Problems with Conze’s Prajñāpāramitā-hṛdaya.” <em>Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies</em> 8 (2015): 28–48. <a href="http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/104">http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/104</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="7abdff0d-b458-43c3-b38d-4e2b26867337" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4al7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “Epithets of the Mantra in the Heart Sutra.” <em>Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies</em> 12 (2017a): 26–57. <a href="http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/155">http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/155</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="840843a2-07ab-498a-b9c6-7ee099ad1986" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4el7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “Form is (Not) Emptiness: The Enigma at the Heart of the Heart Sutra.” <em>Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies</em> 13 (2017b): 52–80. <a href="http://www.jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/164">http://www.jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/164</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="206cfd27-7d8d-4e7c-b01b-28c1de36160a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4il7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.4</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “The Buddhas of the Three Times and the Chinese Origins of the Heart Sutra.” <em>Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies</em> 15 (2018): 9–27. <a href="http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/184">http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/184</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="4450fb27-d314-4ec5-8741-07bce6db3494" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4ml7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.5</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “Xuanzang’s Relationship to the Heart Sūtra in Light of the Fangshan Stele.” <em>Journal of Chinese Buddhist Studies</em> 32 (2019): 1–30. <a href="http://chinesebuddhiststudies.org/previous_issues/jcbs3201_Attwood(1-30).pdf">http://chinesebuddhiststudies.org/previous_issues/jcbs3201_Attwood(1-30).pdf</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="c333fce7-6c05-4733-bac9-c3dba494f3d2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4ql7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.6</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “The History of the Heart Sutra as a Palimpsest.” <em>Pacific World</em>, Series Four, no. 1 (2020): 155–82.</p></div></div></div><div id="74919c7e-08b6-4ece-b3d1-f37b4f5b90b0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_4ul7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.7</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Attwood, Jayarava. “Preliminary Notes on the Extended Heart Sutra in Chinese.” <em>Asian Literature and Translation</em> 8 (1) (2021): 63–85. <a href="https://alt.cardiffuniversitypress.org/articles/abstract/10.18573/alt.53/">https://alt.cardiffuniversitypress.org/articles/abstract/10.18573/alt.53/</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="5ba33073-1cae-4b99-a880-fc908a1a99d4" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_52l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.8</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Conze, Edward. “The Prajñāpāramitā-Hṛdaya Sūtra.” In <em>Thirty Years of Buddhist Studies: Selected Essays</em>, 147–67. Bruno Cassirer, 1967.</p></div></div></div><div id="80f746ba-74a5-44e9-acb5-01242af95b7d" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_56l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.9</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Dalai Lama. <em>Essence of the Heart Sutra: The Dalai Lama’s Heart of Wisdom Teachings</em>. Translated and edited by Geshe Thupten Jinpa. Sommerville: Wisdom Publications, 2015.</p></div></div></div><div id="8514edb1-2218-4d03-8439-4bf749e3502e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5al7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.10</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Herrmann-Pfandt, Adelheid. <em>Die lHan kar ma: ein früher Katalog der ins Tibetische übersetzten buddhistischen Texte</em>. Vienna: Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, 2008.</p></div></div></div><div id="b90921ed-0715-4038-91d4-bd72d6b6e1e6" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5el7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.11</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Horiuchi, Toshio. “Revisiting the ‘Indian’ Commentaries on the Prajñāpāramitāhṛdaya: Vimalamitra’s Interpretation of the ‘Eight Aspects.’ ” <em>Acta Asiatica</em> 121 (2021): 53–81.</p></div></div></div><div id="f6300dd1-742c-4a21-815d-49045bff8610" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5il7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.12</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Shi, Huifeng. “Apocryphal Treatment for Conze’s Heart Problems: ‘Non-attainment,’ ‘Apprehension,’ and ‘Mental Hanging’ in the Prajñāpāramitā.” <em>Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies</em> 6 (2014): 72–105. <a href="http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/75">http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/75</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="67ede31f-85a6-4a4d-a916-06501afa86e0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5ml7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.13</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Ishii, Kōsei (<em>石井 公成</em>). <em>『般若心経』をめぐる諸問題 : ジャン・ナティエ氏の玄奘創作説を疑う</em> [Issues Surrounding the Prajñāpāramitā-hṛdaya: Doubts Concerning Jan Nattier’s Theory of a Composition by Xuanzang]. Indogaku Bukkyōgaku kenkyū <em>印度學佛教學研究 </em>64 (2015): 499–92. Translated by Jeffrey Kotyk.</p></div></div></div><div id="ca298680-254f-47a1-b6c5-90cedde071cc" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5ql7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.14</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Kotyk, Jeffrey. “Chinese State and Buddhist Historical Sources on Xuanzang: Historicity and the Daci’en si sanzang fashi zhuan 大慈恩寺三藏法師傳.” <em>T’oung Pao</em> 105 (2019): 513–44. </p></div></div></div><div id="5351c372-67b9-421b-85f0-2a2a838b9709" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5ul7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.15</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Lopez, Donald S. <em>Elaborations on Emptiness: Uses of the Heart Sūtra</em>. Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1996.</p></div></div></div><div id="0e4c59a6-29f6-47a8-9d7c-141031972cc8" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_62l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.16</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Lusthaus, Dan. “The Heart Sūtra in Chinese Yogācāra: Some Comparative Comments on the Heart Sūtra Commentaries of Wŏnch’ŭk and K’uei-chi.” <em>International Journal of Buddhist Thought and Culture</em> 3 (2003): 59–103.</p></div></div></div><div id="50f6054b-40ee-47df-b27d-91ad751e8227" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_66l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.17</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Nālandā Translation Committee. <em>The Sūtra of the Heart of Transcendent Knowledge</em>. 1980. Online publication. <a href="https://www.nalandatranslation.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Heart-Sutra-for-website.pdf">https://www.nalandatranslation.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Heart-Sutra-for-website.pdf</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="c56cff17-7d5c-464c-a836-150def762f92" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6al7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.18</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Nattier, Jan. “The Heart Sūtra: A Chinese Apocryphal Text?” <em>Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies</em> 15, no. 2 (1992): 153–223.</p></div></div></div><div id="17f260f8-8f7d-493d-8db1-7e3b719dd3b8" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6el7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.19</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Padmakara Translation Group, trans. <em> <a href="https://read.84000.co/translation/toh9.html">The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-five Thousand Lines</a> </em> (<em>Pañca­viṃśati­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā</em>, Toh 9). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2023.</p></div></div></div><div id="83ddd462-3809-46b8-aa9d-f51528884cc6" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6il7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.20</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Silk, Jonathan. <em>The Heart Sutra in Tibetan: A Critical Edition of the Two Recensions Contained in the Kanjur</em>. Wiener Studien zur Tibetologie und Buddhismuskunde, vol. 34. Vienna: Arbeitskreis fur Tibetische und Buddhistische Studien, Universitat Wien, 1994. <a href="https://openphilology.eu/media/pages/publications-jonathan-silk/3568398551-1639738170/authored_1994_heart.pdf">https://openphilology.eu/media/pages/publications-jonathan-silk/3568398551-1639738170/authored_1994_heart.pdf</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="a2c5beab-105f-4412-b2b9-96eba521e8ac" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6ml7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.21</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Sparham, Gareth (2021). “The Heart Sūtra as Dhāraṇī.” <em>Acta Asiatica</em> 121 (2021): 99–125.</p></div></div></div><div id="db761452-91db-4215-9e1b-6b73339892d0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6ql7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.22</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Sparham, Gareth, trans. (2022). <em><a href="https://read.84000.co/translation/toh10.html">The Transcendent Perfection of Wisdom in Eighteen Thousand Lines</a></em> (<em>Aṣṭa­daśa­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā</em>, Toh 10). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2022.</p></div></div></div><div id="e1dd7890-0258-42f0-a7aa-a8cbcab6e2c0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_6ul7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.23</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Sparham, Gareth, trans. (2024). <em><a href="https://read.84000.co/translation/toh8.html">The Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand Lines</a> </em> (<em>Śata­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā</em>, Toh 8). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2024.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><script>$RS("S:5","P:5")</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2d:I[916077,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fb4b456dae69409.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/6165fecb8e0eae36.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1cfd6a6ab8fe5d2f.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/15d7387d42764915.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\"],\"ReaderBodyPanel\"]\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"17:[\"$\",\"$L2d\",null,{\"titles\":[{\"uuid\":\"c7fe8d2d-febd-4334-b119-d9fc80f8a628\",\"title\":\"The Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"4dce0db3-ea50-4fb1-9ac4-51e5a683c658\",\"title\":\"Bhagavatī­prajñā­pāramitā­hṛdaya\",\"language\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"0c42ac50-d218-4380-83d0-85367aa4ed72\",\"title\":\"བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་མ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པའི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"language\":\"bo\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"8a4003f1-c5a4-4022-a25e-16f19b206261\",\"title\":\"bcom ldan ’das ma shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa’i snying po\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"be1ef4ef-326f-405f-ac59-78214e517655\",\"title\":\"Toh 21\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"toh\"},{\"uuid\":\"929827dc-8431-4b63-a8ff-1447b9c44973\",\"title\":\"The Heart of the Illustrious Perfection of Wisdom\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"44151dc1-4436-4016-aac2-f1b40f1d8f25\",\"title\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"71a4d58d-7fb3-4b38-8674-2760b9710877\",\"title\":\"The Essence of the Perfection of Wisdom\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"a48eb69b-a5b5-4ea7-94e3-d84f8cbc06ba\",\"title\":\"shes rab kyi snying po\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"d2ba9589-4dd4-40a2-bc28-9568534f4663\",\"title\":\"《薄伽梵母般若波羅蜜多心經》（大正藏：《佛說聖佛母般若波羅蜜多經》）\",\"language\":\"zh\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"0c265bb9-49af-4db9-9bcd-aaf5308d8ac7\",\"title\":\"Toh 531\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"toh\"}],\"frontMatter\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5219679e-3f3e-47a4-b36d-1ee3a8c6b577\",\"sort\":2,\"type\":\"summaryHeader\",\"label\":\"s.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":7,\"uuid\":\"39c1d084-37be-4e6b-891b-594f4970d323\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Summary\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5f308c16-5020-4977-84db-52331176bfb2\",\"sort\":4,\"type\":\"summary\",\"label\":\"s.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":718,\"uuid\":\"5f308c16-5020-4977-84db-52331176bfb2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In this famous scripture, known popularly as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":45}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c46256f-f692-4ce8-93bf-2ba0b46a6cd5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the Buddha Śākyamuni inspires his senior monk \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":108}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":108,\"end\":117},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e\",\"uuid\":\"f953ed87-3cad-4cfe-b09c-71b8e322b4dd\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to request instructions from the bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":163}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":163,\"end\":177},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"72fad5ab-ad27-4148-b26a-193d06dfa678\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" on the way to practice the perfection of wisdom. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":177,\"end\":227}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":227,\"end\":241},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"5516d7ea-0b03-407c-ac39-157d72d3826f\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" then describes how an aspiring practitioner of the perfection of wisdom must first understand how all phenomena lack an intrinsic nature, which amounts to the realization of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":241,\"end\":416}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"emptiness\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":416,\"end\":425},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c5fa93ab-c81f-4ae8-b5d6-ee67312e9a72\",\"uuid\":\"3507ace9-c7c7-4b4f-ae43-ba97e25f343f\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Next, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":425,\"end\":433}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":433,\"end\":447},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"638c8631-a430-4fe2-b93c-6c0f7871066d\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" reveals a brief mantra that the practitioner can recite as a method for engendering this understanding experientially. Following \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":447,\"end\":577}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":577,\"end\":591},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"e4b7b0f3-01e8-4cb5-bd26-22a9d56518fe\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s teaching, the Buddha offers his endorsement and confirms that this is the foremost way to practice the perfection of wisdom.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":591,\"end\":718}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7efca2bd-29af-4b52-9006-a967931e89fb\",\"sort\":20,\"type\":\"acknowledgmentHeader\",\"label\":\"ac.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"2da30b43-1e99-4306-af85-1d3c5a79b39a\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Acknowledgements\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d9a85105-f035-4da0-ae04-361830933157\",\"sort\":22,\"type\":\"acknowledgment\",\"label\":\"ac.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":389,\"uuid\":\"529517cf-791e-4169-8ef8-dc13e4f31914\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translated by the Dharmachakra Translation Committee under the guidance of Chokyi Nyima Rinpoche. The translation was produced by Catherine Dalton and Andreas Doctor, who also wrote the introduction. Wiesiek Mical compared the translation against the Sanskrit. The translators also wish to thank Jeffrey Kotyk, Jayarava Attwood, and Joshua Capitanio for their helpful comments and advice. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":389}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":389,\"end\":501,\"uuid\":\"941a4c59-b253-4ee3-9905-cfe5482d9b9c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The translation was completed under the patronage and supervision of 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":389,\"end\":501}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"68ace327-8c9c-4dd8-a804-571fb16ddd15\",\"sort\":25,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"i.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":12,\"uuid\":\"a4dce80d-3dbe-4ac6-bd46-0d32124ee71b\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Introduction\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bbaae9e8-5512-44df-9eb5-a5c1c08fdef5\",\"sort\":27,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":758,\"uuid\":\"bbaae9e8-5512-44df-9eb5-a5c1c08fdef5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7deca860-03f9-4146-b5c0-914073e33dd9\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":58},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"76ce43be-d5be-423a-9e2a-d08100ae234a\",\"label\":\"1\",\"uuid\":\"2c81426f-bd3f-4066-b35a-d376420b1e68\",\"start\":58,\"end\":58,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" which today is popularly known simply as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":100}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":115},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"aae05965-d98d-4c6a-8bec-3e64b6f26cda\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":115,\"end\":116},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"3bb043f8-7c8e-4662-85b6-3486e8fed258\",\"label\":\"2\",\"uuid\":\"06682d35-cdd3-47cc-9fb0-42e6d42ffaf8\",\"start\":116,\"end\":116,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" has been cherished, read, and recited by Mahāyāna Buddhists in East and Central Asia for well over a millennium. Over the centuries, scholars and practitioners have continued to find deep meaning in this short scripture and vigorously debated its purpose and practice‍—and even whether to classify it as a sūtra or a tantra. Still today, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":116,\"end\":455}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":455,\"end\":470},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2fc9416b-1121-4d78-897e-1e464eff3d15\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" continues to be recited around the world in monasteries, temples, and meditation centers in a variety of Buddhist traditions. As a result of its popularity, in more recent times the sūtra has been translated into a wide variety of modern languages that are available in print and online.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":470,\"end\":758}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f325aa67-f947-49bf-8d77-4d6f57d00775\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":756,\"uuid\":\"f325aa67-f947-49bf-8d77-4d6f57d00775\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The sūtra takes place on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vulture Peak Mountain\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":46},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"faf044bb-e030-4ea8-9a1f-f12b9b0672d6\",\"uuid\":\"0ce09f15-0ee1-4921-83a0-6b907f3369da\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" near \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":52}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rājagṛha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"00a8c52d-7629-4286-8237-9f6bd87d18d3\",\"uuid\":\"c54bcd10-a62a-449e-8f54-e82cb477f437\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Here the Buddha inspires his senior monk \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":103}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":103,\"end\":112},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34b48087-ac26-49a1-8f0e-71b760f25b7e\",\"uuid\":\"149c0c2c-474f-45f6-9931-a1cbca64f4f0\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to request instructions from the bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":112,\"end\":158}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":158,\"end\":172},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"50a598ed-5a0a-40b8-beb9-f9a47dabd435\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" regarding the practice of the perfection of wisdom.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":224},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"bbfaa8a1-0236-41c5-a42f-f52128e7956a\",\"label\":\"3\",\"uuid\":\"8e9e49d6-9026-4ed2-9d1d-7dc6a8f34386\",\"start\":224,\"end\":224,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Prompted in this way, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":224,\"end\":247}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":247,\"end\":261},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"5099a0b9-a82f-4d1b-b5b0-54309787ad3e\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" describes how an aspiring practitioner of the perfection of wisdom must first understand that all phenomena lack an intrinsic nature and therefore are empty. To manifest this realization in the practitioner, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":261,\"end\":470}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":470,\"end\":484},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"c020cc70-cef2-47e8-8b73-d5d5be718c34\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" reveals a brief mantra to be recited: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":523}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tadyathā gate gate pāragate pārasaṃgate bodhi svāhā.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":523,\"end\":575},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"mantra\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1662054e-e382-45a2-8fa2-b45a1ee427e2\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Following \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":575,\"end\":586}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":586,\"end\":600},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"5108d71a-5e8a-4bcb-8868-8be3d63a4371\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s teaching, the Buddha offers his endorsement of what has been said and confirms that this is indeed the foremost way to practice the perfection of wisdom.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":600,\"end\":756}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"808d4c1e-d306-47a1-916a-b73a3bf93d56\",\"sort\":58,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":568,\"uuid\":\"808d4c1e-d306-47a1-916a-b73a3bf93d56\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In English we speak of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":38},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c3b43ec-5651-4c61-8d80-306c9f92e036\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the singular, but this obscures the fact that‍—more than most Buddhist canonical scriptures‍—this short teaching exists in a variety of versions, recensions, and redactions in multiple canonical languages. Most importantly, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":266}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":266,\"end\":281},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a5bfd2f2-3fd3-42a7-b844-fc004791b8a6\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" exists in both a short and a long version (although the long version is also very brief) in Chinese, Sanskrit, and Tibetan. In East Asia the shorter version, which is also the older one in terms of textual history, became the most popular, while in Tibet the longer version was favored.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":568}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4a9baa2d-199b-48d3-87b4-cf2e92ee3e07\",\"sort\":63,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":15,\"uuid\":\"b62dea8d-998e-4eba-a176-52629789fbed\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Short Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\",\"sort\":65,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2218,\"uuid\":\"ab300509-6a7d-47b3-94e3-24f96394e834\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":36},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"af0087d8-ec84-4761-b530-31d59426a2d4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was first compiled‍—most likely as an abstract of longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras‍—in China sometime in the middle of the seventh century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":36,\"end\":172}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":174},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":174,\"uuid\":\"ad1a07ae-06df-4a3d-982b-e58c3d4a0ced\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":174,\"end\":175},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"14105497-864a-46a2-a6bb-a711c4ad495c\",\"label\":\"4\",\"uuid\":\"ca8856a5-e3da-4c76-a6ab-d1a137b81e63\",\"start\":175,\"end\":175,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Shortly thereafter, it appears that the sūtra was translated from Chinese into Sanskrit. The material used to compile the sūtra was extracted from key passages in Prajñāpāramitā scriptures in Chinese translation, especially Kumārajīva’s (344–413 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":175,\"end\":422}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":422,\"end\":424},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":422,\"end\":424,\"uuid\":\"c4c9d779-5c9a-408c-9028-c0025c976273\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") translation of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":424,\"end\":441}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Twenty-Five Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":441,\"end\":495},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cf11ce93-89ea-4bd5-9acf-3a1e3f60b793\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Taishō 223). These central statements were then framed by an introduction describing the bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":495,\"end\":598}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":598,\"end\":612},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"092063d9-c008-4551-a8ec-1d97e6c063de\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s role as the teacher, and then a concluding mantra, which functioned to encapsulate the blessings of the Prajñāpāramitā teachings.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":612,\"end\":744},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"96186a0e-8e29-45a6-a6fc-cce5c0cfa5ea\",\"label\":\"5\",\"uuid\":\"0283135b-2cfd-4e4e-aff7-7c3f4f362d0e\",\"start\":744,\"end\":744,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" In this way, the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":744,\"end\":779}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":779,\"end\":794},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"dc06bac8-372b-45c1-8cec-35e6a1441eaa\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" combines established Buddhist Prajñāpāramitā scripture with \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":794,\"end\":855}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dhāraṇī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":855,\"end\":862},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":855,\"end\":862,\"uuid\":\"b02c55a7-4bd9-4152-ad75-d567057d4c9e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" practice in an abridged format that is eminently suited for recitation. Notably, at that time in China such scriptural digests summarizing the words of the Buddha (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":862,\"end\":1027}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"buddhavacana\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1027,\"end\":1039},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1027,\"end\":1039,\"uuid\":\"b11dd7e0-169d-45fa-9611-e29807b0c8d9\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") were common, and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1039,\"end\":1058}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1058,\"end\":1073},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"57a8746c-a75b-46bc-ad0d-c9087cafe348\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is certainly not unique in this way.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1073,\"end\":1110},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"359bc88a-cac1-4651-86d4-6cfc9fea8e8b\",\"label\":\"6\",\"uuid\":\"999120f4-0705-4de4-8b68-e06dc4bc31b1\",\"start\":1110,\"end\":1110,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" What is remarkable, however, is the immense importance and popularity the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1110,\"end\":1202}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1202,\"end\":1217},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"81f88fd7-1bdf-4b8a-8c4c-c8ff4aa8ec80\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" came to enjoy in China and the rest of East Asia. When viewed from the perspective of its roots in Prajñāpāramitā literature and its transformative and liberating efficacy in the perception of its many devotees, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1217,\"end\":1430}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1430,\"end\":1445},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"67237d92-36d0-4d6f-bfbd-2e2f691ea842\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" does fulfill important criteria for being a genuine Buddhist scripture. For example, the Mahāyāna sūtra \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1445,\"end\":1550}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Inspiring Determination\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1550,\"end\":1573},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1b2e57dd-0f00-4216-9af7-02dee147bfc5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1573,\"end\":1575}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Adhyāśayasañcodana\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1575,\"end\":1593},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4e872aaf-9d86-4ede-9a40-277f34c27a78\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Toh 69) defines authentic buddhavacana as any discourse\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1593,\"end\":1650},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"1e485bb7-ba1f-4f8d-95d6-35c1844333de\",\"label\":\"7\",\"uuid\":\"563ae0ef-965c-4749-8b70-846cfbf7048e\",\"start\":1650,\"end\":1650,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that fulfils the following four criteria: (1) it must be meaningful, (2) it has to be consistent with the Dharma, (3) it should reduce mental defilements, and (4) it should present the qualities of nirvāṇa as opposed to saṃsāra.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1650,\"end\":1879},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"ace0454d-3ac7-4437-ac2e-388d77808253\",\"label\":\"8\",\"uuid\":\"f633bf19-0c92-414d-b0b0-de4e58374c1e\",\"start\":1879,\"end\":1879,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" In this sense \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1879,\"end\":1894}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1894,\"end\":1909},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e11a10e7-0e9e-4439-ba62-fefc74bb5bf5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is perhaps not so different from many other Mahāyāna scriptures, in particular those of the Prajñāpāramitā family, that likewise were transmitted across a variety of time periods, regions, cultures, and languages‍—constantly in flux, yet ever encapsulating the transcendent aspects of authentic buddhavacana.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1909,\"end\":2218}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3441b1f0-e501-499c-8c80-d7176aa83af9\",\"sort\":105,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.5\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":926,\"uuid\":\"3441b1f0-e501-499c-8c80-d7176aa83af9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Traditionally, the earliest version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":39}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":54},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"596e146a-aa5e-436b-bf74-a0c0dfdc2699\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in Chinese was thought to be Taishō 250, which in traditional sources is described as a translation of Kumārajīva. However, this attribution is generally no longer accepted, and some scholars have placed it later in time‍—some even in the beginning of the eighth century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":326}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":326,\"end\":328},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":326,\"end\":328,\"uuid\":\"73fbb1c8-b7c4-40a5-9ce1-73bc9e787f26\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":328,\"end\":329},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"8779a750-1c7d-4367-8b42-f64ada1c7473\",\"label\":\"9\",\"uuid\":\"359f4616-ffe6-45d7-95ba-1dbd4c276221\",\"start\":329,\"end\":329,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Apart from Taishō 250, the earliest witness for \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":329,\"end\":378}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra’s\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":378,\"end\":395},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"36f5b7a3-7df1-477b-8e11-062b021e9059\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" existence is a famous stone stele, which was discovered in the early twentieth century at the Yunju Temple in the Fangshan region near Beijing. The inscription on this stele is a rendering of the short version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":395,\"end\":609}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":609,\"end\":624},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"75884789-5d49-499c-adb8-f5c8e086b341\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and the colophon is dated to 661. The colophon further states that this is the translation prepared by Xuanzang (i.e., an equivalent of Taishō 251).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":624,\"end\":774},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"84225b71-239c-4976-aec6-10e347f90c1c\",\"label\":\"10\",\"uuid\":\"c71bbace-3220-41db-b27c-4931525a5381\",\"start\":774,\"end\":774,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Of the three shorter versions of the text in Chinese,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":774,\"end\":828},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"75b76cfd-ba35-46ea-9d3c-15447ea9ffac\",\"label\":\"11\",\"uuid\":\"0e66ce25-2515-4e8f-b820-15807713ddad\",\"start\":828,\"end\":828,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" this is the one that has been commonly read and recited across East Asia down to the present day.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":828,\"end\":926}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"14033cbc-7c26-463e-99b1-be8164150c5d\",\"sort\":121,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1042,\"uuid\":\"14033cbc-7c26-463e-99b1-be8164150c5d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In terms of Sanskrit sources, the first rendering of the short sūtra in Sanskrit was likely produced shortly after the compilation of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":134}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":134,\"end\":149},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4f436fd5-8e68-410c-acee-38e67b43a36d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in Chinese in the middle of the seventh century. However, the earliest witness we have of a Sanskrit text is not an actual Sanskrit manuscript, but rather a version with the Sanskrit transliterated into Chinese characters (Taishō 256). This text was likely produced by the famous translator and teacher Amoghavajra (705–74) and can therefore be dated to the eighth century.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":523},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"e26f6b3b-134a-4aec-9e6b-e69c66ee49df\",\"label\":\"12\",\"uuid\":\"03ac96dd-1ef8-4b67-a05d-f471990f0745\",\"start\":523,\"end\":523,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" While multiple Sanskrit manuscripts of the shorter version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":523,\"end\":586}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":586,\"end\":601},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7f90e2c4-07a1-4aba-b94f-67139e80ffcc\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" exist, any dating of such manuscripts is typically fraught with much uncertainty.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":601,\"end\":683},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"61214501-32a6-4883-8d04-81042874777d\",\"label\":\"13\",\"uuid\":\"135076ef-3b2d-46e4-afb2-1ae538ae1415\",\"start\":683,\"end\":683,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Scholars have, however, dated a Sanskrit manuscript of the short version (currently kept in Tokyo National Museum) to the ninth or tenth century, and this appears to be the earliest extant Sanskrit manuscript.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":683,\"end\":893},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"d18f74d1-ccbb-4cef-9494-dd880c8d2bac\",\"label\":\"14\",\"uuid\":\"3fe730dd-362f-4d1c-84c9-4a255562daab\",\"start\":893,\"end\":893,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Tibetan translations of the short sūtra were never included in any of the Kangyurs, but several have been identified among the Dunhuang manuscripts.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":893,\"end\":1042},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"1e4a46d9-68ae-429a-8a9e-4a644aadfc3f\",\"label\":\"15\",\"uuid\":\"74b23c52-09bd-446c-b342-15e85789fda7\",\"start\":1042,\"end\":1042,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cb948a05-93b4-4b7a-8037-7535b06d8f1d\",\"sort\":134,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1101,\"uuid\":\"cb948a05-93b4-4b7a-8037-7535b06d8f1d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In sum, we can conclude that the Chinese version of the short sūtra must have been compiled sometime between 404 (when Kumārajīva completed his translation of Taishō 223) and 661 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":179}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":179,\"end\":181},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":179,\"end\":181,\"uuid\":\"d6e777ae-4eaa-4fc5-a159-ea0817516cec\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (the date on the stone stele), and that the Sanskrit translation was produced soon thereafter.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":181,\"end\":276},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"da13e7fc-2763-45be-a004-2e6226787809\",\"label\":\"16\",\"uuid\":\"f020a810-41b7-44de-9370-7bdedf04e039\",\"start\":276,\"end\":276,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" However, in addition to these mutually distant historical markers, we also have data that place the likely time of compilation much more precisely within just a two-year period from 654–56 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":276,\"end\":466}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":466,\"end\":468},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":466,\"end\":468,\"uuid\":\"ea1082ae-76b6-4102-874a-74c5472c0cb0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". First, 654 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":468,\"end\":481}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":481,\"end\":483},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":481,\"end\":483,\"uuid\":\"d021be52-6917-4175-9224-6593d61468e6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" marks the year when the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":483,\"end\":508}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dhāraṇī­samuccaya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":508,\"end\":525},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d6262f31-736c-4199-a9c3-b4af02cad727\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Taishō 901), which is the likely source of the mantra in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":525,\"end\":584}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":584,\"end\":599},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9d6cc8fc-1e9e-4310-a242-d70796957cfa\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", was translated into Chinese.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":599,\"end\":629},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"b44679ad-cae1-45bf-8636-e822bf3c6d3a\",\"label\":\"17\",\"uuid\":\"b5b6700a-0cb1-4250-baa0-ca074d58ede1\",\"start\":629,\"end\":629,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Second, in Xuanzang’s biography (Taishō 2053, written in the late seventh century) it is mentioned that in 656 Xuanzang offered a gold-lettered version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":629,\"end\":785}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":785,\"end\":800},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7dbb67d4-f4a0-4b46-8a66-a8fd3dc363d4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to the imperial family as a gift. Although the biography is a later source than the stone stele, the date provided in the biography is the earliest placement of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":800,\"end\":962}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":962,\"end\":977},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a3bac59c-be91-4591-9ce8-b317e57cfbaf\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the historical record and this may possibly be the very occasion on which \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":977,\"end\":1055}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1055,\"end\":1070},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f2367cb-68e5-4050-8fc1-8ccd053c753d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was first compiled in Chinese.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1070,\"end\":1101},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"08049e5d-d7eb-4604-af4a-e0619a05c5d4\",\"label\":\"18\",\"uuid\":\"bdb213b8-0275-4544-8462-9a87e8eab1da\",\"start\":1101,\"end\":1101,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3d3ef01d-0034-452c-83f6-7072d4d96aae\",\"sort\":156,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":14,\"uuid\":\"21521acb-4f7c-4c7e-b5bd-c26502f3ca26\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Long Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":14}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d04fdc2a-1fa3-484c-a8d8-55f07510b441\",\"sort\":158,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":550,\"uuid\":\"d04fdc2a-1fa3-484c-a8d8-55f07510b441\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The history of the longer version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"484e82da-ad1d-43ad-9c9e-446a4e95b963\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" presents us with an equally complex picture of textual transmission. Notably, there are at least two distinct longer versions of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":182}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":182,\"end\":197},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3858eb21-b023-424c-b986-365768c213f4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Both longer versions add to the short sūtra by presenting a more extensive, traditional introduction (beginning with the statement “Thus did I hear at one time”) and a conventional concluding section as we generally know them from the Mahāyāna sūtras. As a result, the longer versions appear much more like a typical sūtra than does the short version.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":197,\"end\":550}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3ae45e54-c0b9-43af-b9be-542c00e16e8f\",\"sort\":164,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.9\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":523,\"uuid\":\"3ae45e54-c0b9-43af-b9be-542c00e16e8f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The earliest version of the long sūtra, traditionally dated to 738 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":67}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":69},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":69,\"uuid\":\"0767bb2d-429f-4b86-80d5-6a12904cbfd1\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", is a text that only exists in Chinese (Taishō 252). While the text presents itself as a translation from Sanskrit, it is most likely an early attempt to present the short sūtra in a traditional literary format by adding an introduction and a concluding section, which appear to have been composed directly in Chinese. This version does not seem to have gained much popularity, as its unique introduction was never replicated or copied in other sources.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":523},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"6c9a404a-a7ef-47f4-9225-5f0819760cba\",\"label\":\"19\",\"uuid\":\"c6a284da-6d31-4b46-ac42-15abe908f2db\",\"start\":523,\"end\":523,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ab0fab66-d4f5-4523-b609-c8afdfcabaf2\",\"sort\":169,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.10\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":622,\"uuid\":\"ab0fab66-d4f5-4523-b609-c8afdfcabaf2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The four remaining Chinese versions of the long sūtra (Taishō 253, 254, 255, and 257) are all translations that were produced either from Sanskrit or Tibetan manuscripts.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":170},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"0bd9663f-cd0d-47d4-bd94-f9383154361f\",\"label\":\"20\",\"uuid\":\"28215576-d4c3-46ed-860b-e57c8faf34a6\",\"start\":170,\"end\":170,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Although they each feature certain idiosyncratic elements, all of them clearly belong to the same family in text-historical terms. Unfortunately, there are no surviving Sanskrit manuscripts from the period when these four translations were produced, from the late eighth to the early eleventh century.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":170,\"end\":472},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"b1441bbb-3d26-4a1c-b5b8-338ef397c375\",\"label\":\"21\",\"uuid\":\"5a1666e0-b485-41cd-84d9-a68c14f3b02e\",\"start\":472,\"end\":472,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The earliest Sanskrit witnesses we have of the longer version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":472,\"end\":538}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":538,\"end\":553},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d8991ec2-f0ae-44e2-a638-9f09bfaa92bb\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are Nepalese manuscripts that were produced several centuries later.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":553,\"end\":622}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"29046a65-a333-4fee-a3af-501e04eb0394\",\"sort\":179,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":572,\"uuid\":\"29046a65-a333-4fee-a3af-501e04eb0394\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Just as with the Sanskrit translation of the short sūtra, we also do not know the circumstances in which the Sanskrit text of the longer version first appeared. It must have taken place, however, prior to 788 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":209}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":209,\"end\":211},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":209,\"end\":211,\"uuid\":\"e4c065b7-d279-49ea-8303-affc55622e7a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", when the first Chinese translation from Sanskrit was produced. At around the same time, the two Tibetan translations, which were subsequently included in the Kangyur (see more below), must also have been produced. We can say that with some confidence, since the translation is recorded in the Denkarma catalog of completed translations, which is dated to 812.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":211,\"end\":572},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"03adccb4-b20b-4d29-9eb4-edb306398468\",\"label\":\"22\",\"uuid\":\"f3a0e93f-3205-4a14-9049-e727ac193ae2\",\"start\":572,\"end\":572,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"76fdeff3-d747-4f88-a127-fa6fae9ea0e0\",\"sort\":184,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.12\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":920,\"uuid\":\"76fdeff3-d747-4f88-a127-fa6fae9ea0e0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In the Tengyur collections seven commentaries on the long sūtra by Indian scholars and one by a Chinese scholar are included in Tibetan translation. Some of these commentaries were composed by such well-known names in Tibetan history as Kamalaśīla (740–95), \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":258}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vimalamitra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":258,\"end\":269},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2e715653-ecf6-4079-9c15-46e71fdc107a\",\"uuid\":\"83b89c83-ade5-4937-9e7d-0e25764e563b\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (eighth/ninth c.), and Atīśa (982–1054).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":269,\"end\":310},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"5bc1b348-9861-43f3-9799-5ecdec2cd745\",\"label\":\"23\",\"uuid\":\"40da4474-ea08-4cc8-becb-ccd1487c0209\",\"start\":310,\"end\":310,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The authors of these commentaries were all active from the eighth to the eleventh century and most of them are known to have visited Tibet. Interestingly, the different commentators view\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":310,\"end\":497}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":497,\"end\":513},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e875aea2-1264-407c-bbd5-56bbe0b4dc36\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" through very diverse hermeneutical lenses and interpret it variously through the systems of sūtra, tantra, and even ritual practice (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":513,\"end\":647}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sādhana\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":647,\"end\":654},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":647,\"end\":654,\"uuid\":\"5c1f6f07-2bd1-4646-9b80-28f51fcfb601\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). This great variety of interpretations, combined with the fact that there is no mention of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":654,\"end\":747}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":747,\"end\":762},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c7cda676-e7aa-4437-af69-10ad65a5e64e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in any other source linked to India, makes it seem likely that the commentaries were all composed in Tibet during the sojourns of these Indian masters there.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":762,\"end\":920},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"dc18655b-e514-4b3f-a58f-b4e8453e77bf\",\"label\":\"24\",\"uuid\":\"eca47ba8-4d42-4aed-8210-db371d655336\",\"start\":920,\"end\":920,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0b78f0d6-1373-464c-abbd-9085ff8147f2\",\"sort\":197,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.13\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1025,\"uuid\":\"0b78f0d6-1373-464c-abbd-9085ff8147f2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"It therefore appears that the history of the long sūtra can be told largely as a Sino-Tibetan exchange of ideas and manuscripts, which unfolded during the eighth to the eleventh century. In this regard, there are strong indications that the Dunhuang region was an important center for the exchange of such ideas and manuscripts. Among the scriptural treasures discovered in the Dunhuang caves in the early twentieth century, all of which must date prior to the turn of the eleventh century when the caves at Dunhuang were sealed off, there are numerous manuscripts of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":568}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":568,\"end\":583},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ff0830f6-5797-4cde-9abe-1bcd100b87b6\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in both Chinese and Tibetan. In addition to the shorter versions mentioned above, there are a number of longer versions, and apparently even a few “hybrid” manuscripts that are neither of the standard short or long sūtras.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":583,\"end\":806},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"bb5cc842-1bc6-4198-aa59-79b6e76a757c\",\"label\":\"25\",\"uuid\":\"6d586d3b-38d1-4f3f-94b5-ee4a1efac24a\",\"start\":806,\"end\":806,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Like the Chinese and Sanskrit versions, these Tibetan Dunhuang manuscripts provide a variety of readings, but so far no comparative analyses of these texts, or critical editions of the manuscripts, have been published.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":806,\"end\":1025}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b69c4232-e750-4af9-9aef-908b515dcc23\",\"sort\":202,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":30,\"uuid\":\"1a9071ab-6537-4611-98fa-086f1f247511\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f7d1d6a-61c0-4f64-a847-aaf752dac8d6\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the Kangyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":15,\"end\":30}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23578ae0-738f-47be-a5fd-ad38ab804a1a\",\"sort\":205,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.14\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":629,\"uuid\":\"23578ae0-738f-47be-a5fd-ad38ab804a1a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In Tibet, only the longer version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7d9c1edd-119c-4906-93a3-b3fc2286322d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was included in the various Kangyur collections, where it has been preserved in two recensions, which Jonathan Silk has designated Recension A and Recension B.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":212},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"978942c1-69bd-4548-98c0-cd7653a821a7\",\"label\":\"26\",\"uuid\":\"9d956ed9-d8fd-41f8-bb76-b774b6029ba5\",\"start\":212,\"end\":212,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" These two recensions represent individual manuscript traditions and appear to have been translated into Tibetan by different translators, although the exact details remain unknown.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":212,\"end\":393},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"c4c71011-bb00-4dc2-98ec-b484b8cda947\",\"label\":\"27\",\"uuid\":\"c567e10c-9527-46cf-b4f9-a11381c65e83\",\"start\":393,\"end\":393,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The two recensions vary on several significant points, such as the title of the text, the name of the absorption in which the Buddha rests, the mantra that \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":393,\"end\":550}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Avalokiteśvara\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":550,\"end\":564},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"15f3a5cf-5d86-4439-b06f-5909aae6a9d2\",\"uuid\":\"e72ff549-c308-4f62-80ff-cbef4180af63\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" reveals, and the presence or absence of a translator’s colophon.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":564,\"end\":629}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eb16cd74-fa4c-4c7d-839d-dc65be86ea7f\",\"sort\":215,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.15\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":862,\"uuid\":\"eb16cd74-fa4c-4c7d-839d-dc65be86ea7f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The fact that \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":14}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":14,\"end\":29},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7a2ed6c6-74f1-4332-91e6-163c28a4b376\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" incorporates elements of both sūtra and tantra, and therefore has been variously classified throughout its history, is evident from its placement in the different Kangyur collections, where it often appears twice in both the Tantra section and the Perfection of Wisdom section.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":307},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"325699cb-d7e1-4e0a-a96d-8c39ebf6facc\",\"label\":\"28\",\"uuid\":\"138981f2-f661-4156-a535-5b15101d2b01\",\"start\":307,\"end\":307,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Generally speaking, all Kangyurs include Recension A in their Tantra sections, whereas some Kangyurs, mostly those of the Thempangma (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":307,\"end\":442}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"them spangs ma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":442,\"end\":456},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d7a33abe-aea0-49f3-9f19-c4be635bb9ab\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") branch, also include Recension B in the Perfection of Wisdom section.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":456,\"end\":527},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"57060c94-2672-4be3-9989-e17fa2b7a512\",\"label\":\"29\",\"uuid\":\"8e0fbcc2-2bc0-47ec-b855-f414c9798f9b\",\"start\":527,\"end\":527,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The Kangyurs that belong to the Tshalpa (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":527,\"end\":569}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tshal pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":569,\"end\":577},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":569,\"end\":577,\"uuid\":\"3d499430-b801-4737-b25e-796246a61998\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") branch mostly include the text only once, in the Tantra section.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":577,\"end\":643},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"ef709bb1-0d32-4f67-9032-10e6c597acba\",\"label\":\"30\",\"uuid\":\"cf815dc9-cfb8-4b41-ae90-3609d69e57e8\",\"start\":643,\"end\":643,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" In the Degé Kangyur, however, the text appears in both the Perfection of Wisdom and the Tantra sections, but, unlike the Thempangma Kangyurs, the Degé Kangyur includes Recension A both times, thus omitting Recension B.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":643,\"end\":862},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"d8a2ead0-b089-4899-a452-f38f56f93f93\",\"label\":\"31\",\"uuid\":\"7f83ab05-0e8b-4bfd-8ee7-12239880d0ac\",\"start\":862,\"end\":862,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e7d3dc8c-ddd8-44b2-9455-1cb3bc80d253\",\"sort\":232,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.16\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":986,\"uuid\":\"e7d3dc8c-ddd8-44b2-9455-1cb3bc80d253\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Our translation is based primarily on the version of Recension A that is included in the Degé Kangyur. We have made Recension A our primary focus in order to present in English one important version of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":202}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":202,\"end\":217},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"18ac4d98-5746-445b-bced-8d3884b4ce66\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as it has been transmitted in Tibet since the early ninth century, rather than attempting to edit this version in search of an elusive urtext. However, to give the reader a taste of the differences between the two Tibetan recensions‍—differences that the Tibetans found worthy of preservation in their Kangyurs‍—we have included in the form of notes the most significant variations between the Degé text and the version of Recension B that is included in the Perfection of Wisdom section in the Stok Palace Kangyur.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":217,\"end\":733},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"d6e5fd62-f62c-4989-8cf2-ffa3db620f6c\",\"label\":\"32\",\"uuid\":\"bf003227-edab-48a1-b2ed-856853ca9073\",\"start\":733,\"end\":733,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" We have also attempted, whenever possible, to let our translation be informed by the published Sanskrit editions of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":733,\"end\":850}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":850,\"end\":865},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"40537f5a-04a3-48e0-9025-24ab00d7143f\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the eight commentaries on the text in the Tengyur collections, and the growing scholarly literature on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":865,\"end\":970}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":970,\"end\":985},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b25f12c5-381f-465e-b89d-4fe68c13c8a9\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":985,\"end\":986}}]}]}],\"body\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"da1e7c59-f74c-47df-8b52-f51b5af577ee\",\"sort\":244,\"type\":\"translationHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":15,\"uuid\":\"e19997b7-b679-47fa-b335-4fa2a3d68ebb\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Translation\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b054375a-7b26-43a3-be8d-d3a3f06a1d0b\",\"sort\":245,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.\",\"alignments\":{\"toh531\":{\"folioUuid\":\"35919386-b6cc-4b65-9eca-560424ebe9d2\",\"toh\":\"toh531\",\"tibetan\":\"༄༅༅། །རྒྱ་གར་སྐད་དུ། བྷ་ག་བ་ཏཱི་པྲཛྙཱ་པཱ་ར་མི་ཏཱ་ཧྲྀ་ད་ཡ། བོད་སྐད་དུ། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་མ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པའི་སྙིང་པོ། བམ་པོ་གཅིག་གོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":94,\"volumeNumber\":88},\"toh21\":{\"folioUuid\":\"5bf4c3ad-d4a7-41bb-a371-4525388b64a2\",\"toh\":\"toh21\",\"tibetan\":\"༄༅༅། །རྒྱ་གར་སྐད་དུ། བྷ་ག་བ་ཏཱི་པྲཛྙཱ་པཱ་ར་མི་ཏཱ་ཧྲྀ་ད་ཡ། བོད་སྐད་དུ། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་མ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པའི་སྙིང་པོ། བམ་པོ་གཅིག་གོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":144,\"volumeNumber\":34}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"9e7379f0-4dfa-4d33-9b20-19aff25d0d86\",\"level\":2,\"class\":\"body-title-main\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Heart of the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"900d66c8-caef-469f-911b-98cba686dcea\",\"sort\":251,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"alignments\":{\"toh531\":{\"folioUuid\":\"35919386-b6cc-4b65-9eca-560424ebe9d2\",\"toh\":\"toh531\",\"tibetan\":\"བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་མ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ཕྱག་འཚལ་ལོ། །འདི་སྐད་བདག་གིས་ཐོས་པ་དུས་གཅིག་\\nན། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་རྒྱལ་པོའི་ཁབ་བྱ་རྒོད་ཕུང་པོའི་རི་ལ། དགེ་སློང་གི་དགེ་འདུན་ཆེན་པོ་དང་། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའི་དགེ་འདུན་ཆེན་པོ་དང་ཐབས་ཅིག་ཏུ་བཞུགས་ཏེ། \",\"folioNumber\":94,\"volumeNumber\":88},\"toh21\":{\"folioUuid\":\"5bf4c3ad-d4a7-41bb-a371-4525388b64a2\",\"toh\":\"toh21\",\"tibetan\":\"བཅོམ་\\nལྡན་འདས་མ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ཕྱག་འཚལ་ལོ། །འདི་སྐད་བདག་གིས་ཐོས་པ་དུས་གཅིག་ན། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་རྒྱལ་པོའི་ཁབ་ན་བྱ་རྒོད་ཕུང་པོའི་རི་ལ། དགེ་སློང་གི་དགེ་འདུན་ཆེན་པོ་དང་། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའི་དགེ་འདུན་ཆེན་པོ་དང་ཐབས་ཅིག་[F.145.a]ཏུ་བཞུགས་ཏེ། \",\"folioNumber\":144,\"volumeNumber\":34}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":56,\"uuid\":\"23aa9cd4-627c-4976-9da6-309fb27cbe23\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"624a28bf-492c-47d7-bcb6-3d222c7a301b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"H\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"4d1896b2-dcf3-4b01-8cc6-8bd5e30c9d67\",\"label\":\"33\",\"uuid\":\"9d71df67-1c4e-4592-90b0-c9e194ffdf11\",\"start\":0,\"end\":0,\"location\":\"start\",\"toh\":\"toh21\"},{\"endNote\":\"6085c4ea-7fd1-419b-9ef0-596e57bb2249\",\"label\":\"33\",\"uuid\":\"3a29d810-4c61-4c39-97e8-b05fa1a673b6\",\"start\":0,\"end\":0,\"location\":\"start\",\"toh\":\"toh531\"}],\"start\":0,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"omage to the Perfection of Wisdom, the Blessed Mother!\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1,\"end\":55},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"e08623fc-9546-4c0d-af84-c434fed7f74e\",\"label\":\"34\",\"uuid\":\"7d633d7f-0266-4c86-b8a4-8f108a3195ee\",\"start\":55,\"end\":55,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":56}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":224,\"uuid\":\"60a0f52a-128d-48dd-8568-f67434815edb\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Thus did I hear at one time. The Blessed One was residing on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":117}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vulture Peak Mountain\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":138},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"faf044bb-e030-4ea8-9a1f-f12b9b0672d6\",\"uuid\":\"4818b738-8aa2-4b0c-904f-78e21564e121\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" at \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":138,\"end\":142}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rājagṛha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":142,\"end\":150},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"00a8c52d-7629-4286-8237-9f6bd87d18d3\",\"uuid\":\"6853faa1-ab0d-4801-813a-e452a95af062\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" together with a great saṅgha of monks and a great saṅgha of bodhisattvas.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":150,\"end\":224}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6377055b-2736-4d35-96d2-f5d908c2faae\",\"sort\":260,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.2\",\"alignments\":{\"toh531\":{\"folioUuid\":\"35919386-b6cc-4b65-9eca-560424ebe9d2\",\"toh\":\"toh531\",\"tibetan\":\"དེའི་ཚེ་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ཟབ་མོ་སྣང་བ་ཞེས་བྱ་བའི་ཆོས་ཀྱི་རྣམ་གྲངས་ཀྱི་ཏིང་ངེ་འཛིན་ལ་སྙོམས་པར་ཞུགས་སོ། །\\n\",\"folioNumber\":94,\"volumeNumber\":88},\"toh21\":{\"folioUuid\":\"1e784f79-2f7c-4f40-bbbb-32e8525bf481\",\"toh\":\"toh21\",\"tibetan\":\"དེའི་ཚེ་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ཟབ་མོ་སྣང་བ་ཞེས་བྱ་བའི་ཆོས་ཀྱི་རྣམ་གྲངས་ཀྱི་ཏིང་ངེ་འཛིན་ལ་སྙོམས་པར་ཞུགས་སོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":145,\"volumeNumber\":34}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":120,\"uuid\":\"6377055b-2736-4d35-96d2-f5d908c2faae\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"At that time the Blessed One rested in an absorption on the categories of phenomena called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":91}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"illumination of the profound\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":119},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":119,\"uuid\":\"54d54dcb-0018-4d62-a788-17c70e6bd209\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"distinct\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":119,\"end\":120},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"7e1e441f-579d-4004-b44b-4dc16c3d01b3\",\"label\":\"35\",\"uuid\":\"6668da90-acdb-4953-9bf8-c46fa3a39f9a\",\"start\":120,\"end\":120,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"851efcc7-c043-4084-9a70-a2fc8d947a2e\",\"sort\":265,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.3\",\"alignments\":{\"toh531\":{\"folioUuid\":\"35919386-b6cc-4b65-9eca-560424ebe9d2\",\"toh\":\"toh531\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡང་དེའི་ཚེ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་འཕགས་པ་སྤྱན་རས་གཟིགས་དབང་ཕྱུག་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཟབ་མོ་སྤྱོད་པ་ཉིད་ལ་རྣམ་པར་ལྟ་ཞིང་། ཕུང་པོ་ལྔ་པོ་དེ་དག་ལ་ཡང་རང་བཞིན་གྱིས་སྟོང་པར་རྣམ་པར་ལྟའོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":94,\"volumeNumber\":88},\"toh21\":{\"folioUuid\":\"1e784f79-2f7c-4f40-bbbb-32e8525bf481\",\"toh\":\"toh21\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡང་དེའི་ཚེ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་འཕགས་པ་སྤྱན་རས་གཟིགས་དབང་ཕྱུག་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་\\nཔ་ཟབ་མོ་སྤྱོད་པ་ཉིད་ལ་རྣམ་པར་ལྟ་ཞིང་། ཕུང་པོ་ལྔ་པོ་དེ་དག་ལ་ཡང་རང་བཞིན་གྱིས་སྟོང་པར་རྣམ་པར་ལྟའོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":145,\"volumeNumber\":34}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":199,\"uuid\":\"851efcc7-c043-4084-9a70-a2fc8d947a2e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"At the same time,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"